Thou shalt not bail them;see thou follow me.

1010
00:59:40.100 --> 00:59:42.600
Some bring the murderedbody, some the murderers.

1011
00:59:44.000 --> 00:59:45.730
Let them not speak a word.

1012
00:59:45.730 --> 00:59:48.000
The guilt is plain.

1013
00:59:48.000 --> 00:59:50.530
For by my soul, were thereworse end than death,

1014
00:59:50.530 --> 00:59:52.970
that end upon them shouldbe executed.

1015
00:59:55.430 --> 00:59:58.370
Andronicus, I will entreatthe king.

1016
00:59:58.370 --> 01:00:01.800
Fear not thy sons; theyshall do well enough.

1017
01:00:12.570 --> 01:00:16.530
Come, Lucius, come.

1018
01:00:16.530 --> 01:00:18.800
Stay not to talk withthem.

1019
01:00:26.800 --> 01:00:29.030
Now go tell, and if thytongue can speak,

1020
01:00:29.030 --> 01:00:31.270
who it was that cut thytongue and ravished thee.

1021
01:00:31.270 --> 01:00:34.430
Write down thy mind,bewray thy meaning so,

1022
01:00:34.430 --> 01:00:37.070
and if thy stumps will letthee, play the scribe.

1023
01:00:37.070 --> 01:00:39.770
See how with signs andtokens she can scrowl.

1024
01:00:39.770 --> 01:00:44.370
Go home, call for sweetwater, wash thy hands.

1025
01:00:44.370 --> 01:00:46.330
She hath no tongue to callnor hands to wash.

1026
01:00:46.330 --> 01:00:49.470
And so let's leave her toher silent walks.

1027
01:00:49.470 --> 01:00:51.970
And 'twere my cause, Ishould go hang myself.

1028
01:00:51.970 --> 01:00:54.900
If thou had'st hands tohelp thee knit the cord.

1029
01:01:02.230 --> 01:01:03.900
Who is this?

1030
01:01:03.900 --> 01:01:06.530
My niece, that flies awayso fast?

1031
01:01:06.530 --> 01:01:08.300
Cousin, a word.

1032
01:01:08.300 --> 01:01:09.830
Where is your husband?

1033
01:01:16.470 --> 01:01:18.970
If I do dream, would allmy wealth would wake me.

1034
01:01:18.970 --> 01:01:21.630
If I do wake, some planetstrike me down,

1035
01:01:21.630 --> 01:01:23.800
that I may slumber ineternal sleep.

1036
01:01:23.800 --> 01:01:25.700
Speak, gentle niece.

1037
01:01:28.030 --> 01:01:30.970
What stern, ungentle hand

1038
01:01:30.970 --> 01:01:35.470
hath lopped and hewed andmade thy body bare

1039
01:01:35.470 --> 01:01:38.630
of her two branches, thosesweet ornaments,

1040
01:01:38.630 --> 01:01:42.130
whose circling shadowskings have sought to sleepin?

1041
01:01:43.600 --> 01:01:45.330
Why dost not speak to me?

1042
01:01:47.430 --> 01:01:51.400
Alas, a crimson river ofwarm blood,

1043
01:01:51.400 --> 01:01:53.700
like to a bubblingfountain stirred withwind,

1044
01:01:53.700 --> 01:01:56.130
doth rise and fall betweenthy rosed lips,

1045
01:01:56.130 --> 01:01:58.730
coming and going with thyhoney breath.

1046
01:02:00.300 --> 01:02:03.630
But sure, some Tereus hathdeflowered thee

1047
01:02:03.630 --> 01:02:06.800
and, lest thou should'stdetect him, cut thytongue.

1048
01:02:06.800 --> 01:02:11.330
Ah, now thou turn'st awaythy face for shame.

1049
01:02:11.330 --> 01:02:15.300
And notwithstanding allthis loss of blood

1050
01:02:15.300 --> 01:02:19.700
as from a conduit withthree issuing spouts

1051
01:02:19.700 --> 01:02:22.670
yet do thy cheeks look redas Titan's face

1052
01:02:22.670 --> 01:02:25.230
blushing to be encounteredwith a cloud.

1053
01:02:26.930 --> 01:02:29.230
Shall I speak for thee?

1054
01:02:29.230 --> 01:02:30.770
Shall I say 'tis so?

1055
01:02:33.270 --> 01:02:38.030
O, that I knew thy heartand knew the beast,

1056
01:02:38.030 --> 01:02:40.770
that I might rail at himto ease my mind.

1057
01:02:40.770 --> 01:02:42.830
Sorrow concealed, like anoven stopped,

1058
01:02:42.830 --> 01:02:45.800
doth burn the heart tocinders where it is.

1059
01:02:45.800 --> 01:02:48.630
Fair Philomel, why she butlost her tongue

1060
01:02:48.630 --> 01:02:50.970
and in a tedious samplersewed her mind.

1061
01:02:50.970 --> 01:02:53.930
But, gentle niece, thatmean is cut from thee.

1062
01:02:55.570 --> 01:02:58.470
A craftier Tereus, cousin,hast thou met,

1063
01:02:58.470 --> 01:03:00.900
for he hath cut thy prettyfingers off

1064
01:03:00.900 --> 01:03:03.000
that could have bettersewed than Philomel.

1065
01:03:04.330 --> 01:03:07.070
O, had the monster seenthose lily hands

1066
01:03:07.070 --> 01:03:09.900
tremble like aspen leavesupon the lute

1067
01:03:09.900 --> 01:03:12.530
and make the silkenstrings delight to kissthem,

1068
01:03:12.530 --> 01:03:15.500
he would not then havetouched them for his life.

1069
01:03:17.730 --> 01:03:19.900
Or had he heard theheavenly harmony

1070
01:03:19.900 --> 01:03:22.370
which that sweet, sweettongue hath made,

1071
01:03:22.370 --> 01:03:25.100
he would have dropped hisknife and fell asleep

1072
01:03:25.100 --> 01:03:27.730
as Cerberus at theThracian poet's feet.

1073
01:03:30.630 --> 01:03:36.130
Come, let us go and makethy father blind,

1074
01:03:36.130 --> 01:03:40.230
for such a sight willblind a father's eye.

1075
01:03:41.330 --> 01:03:44.000
When one hour's storm willdrown the fragrant meads,

1076
01:03:44.000 --> 01:03:47.800
what will whole months oftears thy father's eyes?

1077
01:03:50.100 --> 01:03:55.230
Do not draw back, for wewill mourn with thee.

1078
01:03:57.900 --> 01:04:02.670
O, could our mourning easethy misery.

1079
01:04:09.530 --> 01:04:14.870
Hear me, grave fathers,noble tribunes, stay.

1080
01:04:14.870 --> 01:04:18.030
For pity on mine age,whose youth was spent

1081
01:04:18.030 --> 01:04:21.600
in dangerous wars whilstyou securely slept;

1082
01:04:21.600 --> 01:04:24.600
for all my blood in Rome'sgreat quarrel shed,

1083
01:04:24.600 --> 01:04:26.700
for all the frosty nightsthat I have watched,

1084
01:04:26.700 --> 01:04:29.000
and for these bittertears, which now you see

1085
01:04:29.000 --> 01:04:31.370
filling the aged wrinklesin my cheeks,

1086
01:04:31.370 --> 01:04:34.130
be pitiful to my condemnedsons,

1087
01:04:34.130 --> 01:04:37.300
whose souls are notcorrupted as 'tis thought.

1088
01:04:37.300 --> 01:04:39.770
For two and twenty sons Inever wept,

1089
01:04:39.770 --> 01:04:42.400
because they died inhonor's lofty bed.

1090
01:04:42.400 --> 01:04:45.830
For these, tribunes, inthe dust I write

1091
01:04:45.830 --> 01:04:48.900
my heart's deep languorand my soul's sad tears.

1092
01:04:48.900 --> 01:04:52.000
Let my tears staunch theearth's dry appetite.

1093
01:04:52.000 --> 01:04:55.600
My sons' sweet blood willmake it shame and blush.

1094
01:04:55.600 --> 01:04:58.470
O, earth, I will befriendthee more with rain

1095
01:04:58.470 --> 01:05:01.070
than youthful April shallwith all his showers.

1096
01:05:01.070 --> 01:05:03.100
In summer's drought I'lldrop upon thee still.

1097
01:05:03.100 --> 01:05:05.530
In winter with warm tearsI'll melt the snow

1098
01:05:05.530 --> 01:05:08.030
and keep eternalspringtime on thy face,

1099
01:05:08.030 --> 01:05:11.570
so thou refuse to drink mydear sons' blood.

1100
01:05:12.530 --> 01:05:15.230
O, reverend tribunes,gentle aged men,

1101
01:05:15.230 --> 01:05:19.200
unbind my sons, reversethe doom of death,

1102
01:05:19.200 --> 01:05:21.100
and let me say that neverwept before,

1103
01:05:21.100 --> 01:05:23.800
my tears are nowprevailing orators.

1104
01:05:23.800 --> 01:05:25.270
O, noble father, youlament in vain.

1105
01:05:25.270 --> 01:05:26.800
The tribunes hear you not.

1106
01:05:26.800 --> 01:05:29.300
No man is by, and yourecount your sorrows to astone.

1107
01:05:29.300 --> 01:05:33.030
Ah, Lucius, for thybrothers let me plead.

1108
01:05:33.030 --> 01:05:35.400
Grave tribunes, once moreI entreat of you.

1109
01:05:35.400 --> 01:05:38.200
My gracious lord, notribune hears you speak.

1110
01:05:40.770 --> 01:05:43.100
Why, 'tis no matter, man.

1111
01:05:43.100 --> 01:05:45.830
If they did hear, theywould not mark me.

1112
01:05:45.830 --> 01:05:48.270
If they did mark, theywould not pity me.

1113
01:05:48.270 --> 01:05:52.900
Yet plead I must, andbootless unto them.

1114
01:05:52.900 --> 01:05:56.070
Therefore I tell mysorrows to the stones,

1115
01:05:56.070 --> 01:05:58.600
who though they cannotanswer my distress,

1116
01:05:58.600 --> 01:06:01.900
yet in some sort, they arebetter than the tribunes,

1117
01:06:01.900 --> 01:06:05.730
for that they will notintercept my tale.

1118
01:06:05.730 --> 01:06:08.970
When I do weep, theyhumbly at my feet

1119
01:06:08.970 --> 01:06:14.230
receive my tears and seemto weep with me.

1120
01:06:14.230 --> 01:06:17.330
And were they but attiredin grave weeds,

1121
01:06:17.330 --> 01:06:21.070
Rome could afford notribunes like to these.

1122
01:06:21.070 --> 01:06:26.370
A stone is soft as wax,tribunes more hard thanstones.

1123
01:06:26.370 --> 01:06:30.770
A stone is silent andoffendeth not,

1124
01:06:30.770 --> 01:06:37.530
and tribunes with theirtongues doom men to death.

1125
01:06:41.030 --> 01:06:43.770
But wherefore stand'stthou with thy weapondrawn?

1126
01:06:43.770 --> 01:06:45.830
To rescue my two brothersfrom their death,

1127
01:06:45.830 --> 01:06:48.230
for which attempt thejudges have pronounced

1128
01:06:48.230 --> 01:06:50.300
my everlasting doom ofbanishment.

1129
01:06:50.300 --> 01:06:54.770
O, happy man, they havebefriended thee.

1130
01:06:54.770 --> 01:06:56.970
Why, foolish Lucius, dostthou not perceive

1131
01:06:56.970 --> 01:06:59.670
that Rome is but awilderness of tigers?

1132
01:06:59.670 --> 01:07:01.130
Tigers must prey,

1133
01:07:01.130 --> 01:07:04.330
and Rome affords no preybut me and mine.

1134
01:07:04.330 --> 01:07:05.430
How happy art thou then,

1135
01:07:05.430 --> 01:07:07.930
from these devourers to bebanished?

1136
01:07:07.930 --> 01:07:11.270
But who comes with mybrother Marcus here?

1137
01:07:11.270 --> 01:07:14.700
Titus, prepare thine agedeyes to weep

1138
01:07:14.700 --> 01:07:17.130
or, if not so, thy nobleheart to break.

1139
01:07:17.130 --> 01:07:19.630
I bring consuming sorrowto thine age.

1140
01:07:19.630 --> 01:07:21.200
Will it consume me?

1141
01:07:21.200 --> 01:07:22.730
Let me see it, then.

1142
01:07:22.730 --> 01:07:25.770
This was thy daughter.

1143
01:07:29.970 --> 01:07:33.170
Why, Marcus, so she is.

1144
01:07:33.170 --> 01:07:34.870
Ay me; this object killsme.

1145
01:07:34.870 --> 01:07:37.900
Fainthearted boy, ariseand look on her.

1146
01:07:39.400 --> 01:07:42.170
Speak, Lavinia!

1147
01:07:43.400 --> 01:07:45.270
What accursed hand

1148
01:07:45.270 --> 01:07:49.170
hath made thee handless inthy father's sight?

1149
01:07:49.170 --> 01:07:51.100
What fool hath added waterto the sea

1150
01:07:51.100 --> 01:07:53.870
or brought a fagot tobright-burning Troy?

1151
01:07:53.870 --> 01:07:56.130
My grief was at the heightbefore thou came'st,

1152
01:07:56.130 --> 01:07:59.200
and now like Nilus itdisdaineth bounds.

1153
01:07:59.200 --> 01:08:02.730
Give me a sword; I'll chopoff my hands too,

1154
01:08:02.730 --> 01:08:06.030
for they have fought forRome, and all in vain,

1155
01:08:06.030 --> 01:08:09.970
and they have nursed thiswoe in feeding life.

1156
01:08:09.970 --> 01:08:12.600
In bootless prayer havethey been held up,

1157
01:08:12.600 --> 01:08:15.900
and they have served me toeffectless use.

1158
01:08:15.900 --> 01:08:17.630
Now all the service Irequire of them

1159
01:08:17.630 --> 01:08:19.900
is that the one may helpto cut the other.

1160
01:08:21.670 --> 01:08:24.770
'Tis well, Lavinia, thatthou hast no hands,

1161
01:08:24.770 --> 01:08:29.300
for hands to do Romeservice is but vain.

1162
01:08:29.300 --> 01:08:34.030
Speak, gentle sister, whohath martyred thee?

1163
01:08:34.030 --> 01:08:35.970
O, that delightful engineof her thoughts

1164
01:08:35.970 --> 01:08:37.870
that blabbed them withsuch pleasing eloquence

1165
01:08:37.870 --> 01:08:40.270
is torn from forth thatpretty hollow cage,

1166
01:08:40.270 --> 01:08:42.030
where like a sweet,melodious bird,

1167
01:08:42.030 --> 01:08:45.900
it sang sweet, variednotes, enchanting everyear.

1168
01:08:45.900 --> 01:08:48.970
O, say thou for her, whohath done this deed?

1169
01:08:48.970 --> 01:08:51.470
O, thus I found herstraying in the park,

1170
01:08:51.470 --> 01:08:53.530
seeking to hide herself asdoth the deer

1171
01:08:53.530 --> 01:08:56.330
that hath received someunrecuring wound.

1172
01:08:56.330 --> 01:09:01.830
It was my deer, and hethat wounded her

1173
01:09:01.830 --> 01:09:05.230
hath hurt me more than hadhe killed me dead;

1174
01:09:06.300 --> 01:09:10.700
for now I stand as oneupon a rock

1175
01:09:10.700 --> 01:09:13.670
environed with awilderness of sea

1176
01:09:13.670 --> 01:09:18.530
who marks the waxing tidegrow wave by wave,

1177
01:09:18.530 --> 01:09:21.470
ever expecting when someenvious surge

1178
01:09:21.470 --> 01:09:24.070
will in his brinish bowelsswallow him.

1179
01:09:25.270 --> 01:09:29.200
This way to death mywretched sons are gone.

1180
01:09:29.200 --> 01:09:31.730
Here stands my other son,a banished man,

1181
01:09:31.730 --> 01:09:35.100
and here my brother,weeping at my woes.

1182
01:09:35.100 --> 01:09:38.300
But that which gives mysoul the greatest spurn

1183
01:09:38.300 --> 01:09:44.000
is dear Lavinia, dearerthan my soul.

1184
01:09:44.000 --> 01:09:46.800
Had I but seen thy picturein this plight,

1185
01:09:46.800 --> 01:09:49.130
it would have madded me.

1186
01:09:49.130 --> 01:09:54.030
What shall I do, now Ibehold thy lifely body so?

1187
01:09:56.470 --> 01:10:01.400
Thou hast no hands to wipeaway thy tears,

1188
01:10:01.400 --> 01:10:04.330
nor tongue to tell me whohath martyred thee.

1189
01:10:04.330 --> 01:10:08.800
Thy husband, he is dead,and for his death

1190
01:10:08.800 --> 01:10:13.230
thy brothers are condemnedand dead by this.

1191
01:10:14.630 --> 01:10:16.230
O, Marcus.

1192
01:10:18.030 --> 01:10:20.230
O, son Lucius, look onher.

1193
01:10:20.230 --> 01:10:24.570
When I did name herbrothers, then fresh tears

1194
01:10:24.570 --> 01:10:28.170
stood on her cheeks, asdoth the honey dew

1195
01:10:28.170 --> 01:10:31.770
upon a gathered lilyalmost withered.

1196
01:10:31.770 --> 01:10:34.370
Perchance she weepsbecause they killed herhusband;

1197
01:10:34.370 --> 01:10:36.700
perchance because sheknows them innocent.

1198
01:10:36.700 --> 01:10:39.600
If they did kill thyhusband, then be joyful,

1199
01:10:39.600 --> 01:10:42.530
because the law hath takenrevenge on them.

1200
01:10:42.530 --> 01:10:46.870
No, no; they would not doso vile a deed.

1201
01:10:46.870 --> 01:10:49.900
Witness the sorrow thattheir sister makes.

1202
01:10:59.470 --> 01:11:07.030
Gentle Lavinia, let mekiss thy lips,

1203
01:11:07.030 --> 01:11:11.500
or give some sign how Imay do thee ease.

1204
01:11:18.170 --> 01:11:21.170
Shall thy good uncle andthy brother Lucius

1205
01:11:21.170 --> 01:11:24.100
and thou and I sit roundabout some fountain,

1206
01:11:24.100 --> 01:11:26.730
looking all downwards tobehold our cheeks,

1207
01:11:26.730 --> 01:11:30.100
how they are stained, likemeadows yet not dry

1208
01:11:30.100 --> 01:11:32.970
with miry slime left onthem by a flood?

1209
01:11:32.970 --> 01:11:36.300
And in that fountain shallwe gaze so long,

1210
01:11:36.300 --> 01:11:39.800
till the fresh taste betaken from that clearness

1211
01:11:39.800 --> 01:11:43.770
and made a brine pit withour bitter tears?

1212
01:11:45.430 --> 01:11:49.100
Or shall we cut away ourhands like thine?

1213
01:11:49.100 --> 01:11:51.830
Or shall we bite ourtongues and in dumb shows

1214
01:11:51.830 --> 01:11:53.970
pass the remainder of ourhateful days?

1215
01:11:53.970 --> 01:11:55.630
What shall we do?

1216
01:11:57.370 --> 01:12:00.730
Let us that have ourtongues plot some device

1217
01:12:00.730 --> 01:12:04.670
of further misery to makeus wondered at in time tocome.

1218
01:12:04.670 --> 01:12:06.500
Sweet father, cease yourtears,

1219
01:12:06.500 --> 01:12:10.030
for at your grief see howmy wretched sister sobsand weeps.

1220
01:12:10.030 --> 01:12:11.730
Patience, dear niece.

1221
01:12:11.730 --> 01:12:13.730
Good Titus, dry thineeyes.

1222
01:12:15.070 --> 01:12:19.700
O, Marcus, brother Marcus,

1223
01:12:19.700 --> 01:12:23.030
well I wot thy napkincannot drink a tear ofmine,

1224
01:12:23.030 --> 01:12:26.430
for thou, poor man, hathdrowned it with thine own.

1225
01:12:26.430 --> 01:12:30.470
Ah, my Lavinia, I willwipe thy cheeks.

1226
01:12:30.470 --> 01:12:33.800
Mark, Marcus, mark.

1227
01:12:33.800 --> 01:12:37.930
I understand her signs.

1228
01:12:37.930 --> 01:12:40.630
Had she a tongue to speak,now would she say that

1229
01:12:40.630 --> 01:12:42.870
to her brother which Isaid to thee.

1230
01:12:42.870 --> 01:12:46.170
His napkin, with his truetears all bewet,

1231
01:12:46.170 --> 01:12:49.130
can do no service on hersorrowful cheeks.

1232
01:12:53.370 --> 01:12:59.770
O, what a sympathy of woeis this,

1233
01:12:59.770 --> 01:13:03.300
as far from help as Limbois from bliss.

1234
01:13:10.570 --> 01:13:11.900
Titus Andronicus,

1235
01:13:11.900 --> 01:13:14.500
my lord, the emperor,sends thee this word:

1236
01:13:14.500 --> 01:13:17.630
that if thou love thysons, let Marcus, Lucius,

1237
01:13:17.630 --> 01:13:20.070
or thyself, old Titus, orany one of you,

1238
01:13:20.070 --> 01:13:22.630
chop off your hand andsend it to the king.

1239
01:13:22.630 --> 01:13:25.970
He for the same will sendthee hither both thy sonsalive,

1240
01:13:25.970 --> 01:13:28.700
and that shall be theransom for their fault.

1241
01:13:28.700 --> 01:13:30.770
O, gracious emperor.

1242
01:13:30.770 --> 01:13:32.030
O, gentle Aaron.

1243
01:13:32.030 --> 01:13:33.800
Did ever raven sing solike a lark

1244
01:13:33.800 --> 01:13:36.200
to bring sweet tidings ofthe sun's uprise?

1245
01:13:36.200 --> 01:13:38.230
With all my heart, I'llsend the emperor my hand.

1246
01:13:38.230 --> 01:13:40.400
Good Aaron, will thou helpto chop it off?

1247
01:13:40.400 --> 01:13:42.330
Stay, father, for thatnoble hand of thine

1248
01:13:42.330 --> 01:13:44.770
that hath thrown down somany enemies shall not besent.

1249
01:13:44.770 --> 01:13:46.270
My hand will serve theturn.

1250
01:13:46.270 --> 01:13:48.030
My youth can better sparemy blood than you,

1251
01:13:48.030 --> 01:13:50.070
and therefore mine shallsave my brothers' lives.

1252
01:13:50.070 --> 01:13:51.770
Which of your hands hathnot defended Rome

1253
01:13:51.770 --> 01:13:53.400
and reared aloft thebloody battle-ax,

1254
01:13:53.400 --> 01:13:55.170
writing destruction on theenemy's castle?

1255
01:13:55.170 --> 01:13:56.630
O, none of both but are ofhigh desert.

1256
01:13:56.630 --> 01:13:58.170
My hand hath been butidle.

1257
01:13:58.170 --> 01:14:00.800
Let it serve to ransom mytwo nephews from theirdeath.

1258
01:14:00.800 --> 01:14:02.500
Then have I kept it to aworthy end.

1259
01:14:02.500 --> 01:14:05.200
Nay, come, agree whosehand shall go along,

1260
01:14:05.200 --> 01:14:06.830
for fear they die beforetheir pardon come.

1261
01:14:06.830 --> 01:14:07.930
My hand shall go.

1262
01:14:07.930 --> 01:14:09.030
By heaven, it shall notgo.

1263
01:14:09.030 --> 01:14:10.470
Sirs, strive no more.

1264
01:14:10.470 --> 01:14:13.230
Such withered herbs asthese are meet forplucking up,

1265
01:14:13.230 --> 01:14:14.430
and therefore mine.

1266
01:14:14.430 --> 01:14:16.130
Sweet father, if I shallbe thought thy son,

1267
01:14:16.130 --> 01:14:17.830
let me redeem my brothersboth from death.

1268
01:14:17.830 --> 01:14:19.200
And for thy father's sakeand mother's care,

1269
01:14:19.200 --> 01:14:21.170
now let me show abrother's love to thee.

1270
01:14:21.170 --> 01:14:23.830
Agree between you; I willspare my hand.

1271
01:14:23.830 --> 01:14:24.930
Then I'll go fetch an ax.

1272
01:14:24.930 --> 01:14:26.130
I will use the ax.

1273
01:14:26.130 --> 01:14:28.470
Come hither, Aaron; I'lldeceive them both.

1274
01:14:28.470 --> 01:14:30.770
Lend me thy hand, and Iwill give thee mine.

1275
01:14:34.730 --> 01:14:37.900
If that be called deceit,I will be honest

1276
01:14:37.900 --> 01:14:41.070
and never whilst I livedeceive men so.

1277
01:14:41.070 --> 01:14:44.830
But I'll deceive thee inanother sort,

1278
01:14:44.830 --> 01:14:48.730
and that thou say ere halfan hour pass.

1279
01:15:06.270 --> 01:15:08.630
Now strive no more!

1280
01:15:08.630 --> 01:15:11.130
What shall be isdispatched.

1281
01:15:14.030 --> 01:15:17.570
Good Aaron, send HisMajesty my hand.

1282
01:15:17.570 --> 01:15:19.100
Tell him it was a hand

1283
01:15:19.100 --> 01:15:22.070
that warded him fromthousand dangers.

1284
01:15:22.070 --> 01:15:23.630
Bid him bury it.

1285
01:15:23.630 --> 01:15:26.370
More hath it merited; thatlet it have.

1286
01:15:29.130 --> 01:15:31.870
As for my sons, say Iaccount of them

1287
01:15:31.870 --> 01:15:36.630
as jewels purchased at aneasy price,

1288
01:15:36.630 --> 01:15:41.630
and yet dear too, becauseI bought mine own.

1289
01:15:41.630 --> 01:15:45.500
I go, Andronicus, and forthy hand

1290
01:15:45.500 --> 01:15:48.770
look by and by to have thysons with thee.

1291
01:15:50.470 --> 01:15:52.570
Their heads, I mean.

1292
01:15:52.570 --> 01:15:55.330
O, how this villainy dothfat me

1293
01:15:55.330 --> 01:15:57.730
with the very thoughts ofit.

1294
01:15:57.730 --> 01:16:03.200
Let fools do good and fairmen call for grace.

1295
01:16:03.200 --> 01:16:07.330
Aaron will have his soulblack like his face.

1296
01:16:09.830 --> 01:16:14.800
O, here I lift this onehand up to heaven

1297
01:16:14.800 --> 01:16:18.070
and bow this feeble ruinto the earth.

1298
01:16:18.070 --> 01:16:23.970
If any power pitieswretched tears, to that Icall!

1299
01:16:25.330 --> 01:16:27.770
What, wouldst thou kneelwith me?

1300
01:16:27.770 --> 01:16:29.670
Do, then, dear heart,

1301
01:16:29.670 --> 01:16:32.530
for heaven shall hear ourprayers.

1302
01:16:32.530 --> 01:16:36.570
Or with our tears, we'llbreathe the welkin dim

1303
01:16:36.570 --> 01:16:39.470
and stain the sun withfog, as sometime clouds

1304
01:16:39.470 --> 01:16:41.730
when they do hug him intheir melting bosoms.

1305
01:16:41.730 --> 01:16:43.830
O, brother, speak withpossibility,

1306
01:16:43.830 --> 01:16:46.400
and do not break intothese deep extremes.

1307
01:16:46.400 --> 01:16:48.830
Are not my sorrows deep?

1308
01:16:48.830 --> 01:16:52.930
Having no limit, be thenmy passions limitless withthem.

1309
01:16:52.930 --> 01:16:55.270
But yet let reason governthy lament.

1310
01:16:55.270 --> 01:16:58.070
If there were reason forthese miseries,

1311
01:16:58.070 --> 01:17:01.030
then into limits could Ibind my woes.

1312
01:17:02.400 --> 01:17:06.100
When heaven doth weep,doth not the eartho'erflow?

1313
01:17:07.200 --> 01:17:10.170
If the winds rage, dothnot the sea wax mad,

1314
01:17:10.170 --> 01:17:13.470
threatening the welkinwith his big-swollen face?

1315
01:17:13.470 --> 01:17:17.200
And wilt thou have areason for this coil?

1316
01:17:18.430 --> 01:17:20.470
I am the sea!

1317
01:17:21.200 --> 01:17:24.570
Hark how her sighs doblow.

1318
01:17:24.570 --> 01:17:28.130
She is the weeping welkin,I the earth.

1319
01:17:28.130 --> 01:17:31.930
Then must my sea be movedwith her sighs.

1320
01:17:31.930 --> 01:17:35.100
Then must my earth withher continual tears

1321
01:17:35.100 --> 01:17:39.670
become a deluge,overflowed and drowned.

1322
01:17:39.670 --> 01:17:44.600
For why my bowels cannothide her woes,

1323
01:17:44.600 --> 01:17:47.530
but like a drunkard must Ivomit them.

1324
01:17:49.430 --> 01:17:54.870
Then give me leave, forlosers will have leave

1325
01:17:54.870 --> 01:17:58.730
to ease their stomachswith their bitter tongues.

1326
01:18:00.600 --> 01:18:05.400
Worthy Andronicus, ill artthou repaid

1327
01:18:05.400 --> 01:18:08.600
for that good hand thousent'st the emperor.

1328
01:18:09.930 --> 01:18:14.800
Here are the heads of thytwo noble sons,

1329
01:18:14.800 --> 01:18:21.930
and here's thy hand, inscorn to thee sent back

1330
01:18:21.930 --> 01:18:26.970
thy grief their sports,thy resolution mocked,

1331
01:18:26.970 --> 01:18:30.200
that woe is me to thinkupon thy woes,

1332
01:18:30.200 --> 01:18:33.930
more than remembrance ofmy father's death.

1333
01:18:54.270 --> 01:18:56.630
Now let hot Etna cool inSicily,

1334
01:18:56.630 --> 01:18:59.030
and be my heart anever-burning hell.

1335
01:18:59.030 --> 01:19:02.570
These miseries are morethan may be borne.

1336
01:19:02.570 --> 01:19:05.570
To weep with them thatweep doth ease some deal,

1337
01:19:05.570 --> 01:19:08.430
but sorrow flouted at isdouble death.

1338
01:19:10.530 --> 01:19:14.100
Ah, that this sight shouldmake so deep a wound,

1339
01:19:14.100 --> 01:19:17.470
and yet detested life notshrink thereat.

1340
01:19:17.470 --> 01:19:21.670
That ever death should letlife bear his name

1341
01:19:21.670 --> 01:19:25.070
where life hath no moreinterest but to breathe.

1342
01:19:25.930 --> 01:19:28.430
Alas, poor heart, thatkiss is comfortless

1343
01:19:28.430 --> 01:19:31.170
as frozen water to astarved snake.

1344
01:19:33.730 --> 01:19:38.830
When will this fearfulslumber have an end?

1345
01:19:38.830 --> 01:19:42.030
Now farewell, flattery.

1346
01:19:42.030 --> 01:19:43.570
Die, Andronicus.

1347
01:19:43.570 --> 01:19:45.070
Thou dost not slumber.

1348
01:19:45.070 --> 01:19:48.370
See thy two sons' heads,thy warlike hand,

1349
01:19:48.370 --> 01:19:51.070
thy mangled daughter here,thy other banished son

1350
01:19:51.070 --> 01:19:53.330
with this dear sightstruck pale and bloodless,

1351
01:19:53.330 --> 01:19:54.630
and thy brother, I,

1352
01:19:54.630 --> 01:19:57.930
even like a stony image,cold and numb.

1353
01:19:57.930 --> 01:20:00.700
Ah! Now no more will Icontrol thy griefs.

1354
01:20:00.700 --> 01:20:02.600
Rent off thy silver hair,thy other hand

1355
01:20:02.600 --> 01:20:05.100
gnawing with thy teeth,and be this dismal sight

1356
01:20:05.100 --> 01:20:07.700
the closing up of our mostwretched eyes.

1357
01:20:08.570 --> 01:20:10.270
This is a time to storm!

1358
01:20:10.270 --> 01:20:11.930
Why art thou still?

1359
01:20:11.930 --> 01:20:14.300
Ha, ha, ha.

1360
01:20:14.300 --> 01:20:15.430
Why dost thou laugh?

1361
01:20:15.430 --> 01:20:17.270
It fits not with thishour.

1362
01:20:19.270 --> 01:20:25.600
Why, I have not anothertear to shed.

1363
01:20:27.100 --> 01:20:33.970
Besides, this sorrow is anenemy

1364
01:20:33.970 --> 01:20:36.370
and would usurp upon mywatery eyes

1365
01:20:36.370 --> 01:20:39.270
and make them blind withtributary tears.

1366
01:20:39.270 --> 01:20:43.500
Then which way shall Ifind Revenge's cave?

1367
01:20:44.870 --> 01:20:48.270
For these two heads doseem to speak to me,

1368
01:20:48.270 --> 01:20:51.830
and threat me, I shallnever come to bliss

1369
01:20:51.830 --> 01:20:54.700
till all these mischiefsbe returned again,

1370
01:20:54.700 --> 01:20:57.400
even in their throatswhich have committed them.

1371
01:21:01.670 --> 01:21:04.130
Come, let me see what taskI have to do.

1372
01:21:06.330 --> 01:21:08.900
You heavy people, circleme about,

1373
01:21:08.900 --> 01:21:11.870
that I may turn me to eachone of you

1374
01:21:11.870 --> 01:21:16.970
and swear upon my soul toright your wrongs.

1375
01:21:37.230 --> 01:21:39.100
The vow is made.

1376
01:21:42.370 --> 01:21:48.070
Marcus, take thou a head,

1377
01:21:48.070 --> 01:21:51.970
and in this hand the otherwill I bear.

1378
01:21:51.970 --> 01:21:54.830
Lavinia, thou shalt beemployed in this.

1379
01:21:54.830 --> 01:21:59.270
Bear thou my hand, sweetwench, between thy teeth.

1380
01:21:59.270 --> 01:22:01.600
As for thee, boy, go, getthee from my sight.

1381
01:22:01.600 --> 01:22:03.970
Thou art an exile, andthou must not stay.

1382
01:22:05.700 --> 01:22:08.630
Hie to the Goths and raisean army there.

1383
01:22:10.530 --> 01:22:14.930
And if you love me and Ithink it so

1384
01:22:14.930 --> 01:22:19.630
let's kiss and part, forwe have much to do.

1385
01:22:34.930 --> 01:22:38.000
Farewell, Andronicus, mynoble father,

1386
01:22:38.000 --> 01:22:41.300
the woefullest man thatever lived in Rome.

1387
01:22:43.130 --> 01:22:47.530
Farewell, proud Rome, tillLucius come again.

1388
01:22:48.630 --> 01:22:51.970
He loves his pledgesdearer than his life.

1389
01:22:53.400 --> 01:22:57.730
Farewell, Lavinia, mynoble sister.

1390
01:22:57.730 --> 01:23:01.500
O, would thou wert as thoutofore hast been.

1391
01:23:01.500 --> 01:23:06.270
But now nor Lucius norLavinia lives

1392
01:23:06.270 --> 01:23:09.270
but in oblivion andhateful griefs.

1393
01:23:10.970 --> 01:23:14.470
If Lucius live, he willrequite your wrongs

1394
01:23:14.470 --> 01:23:17.830
and make proud Saturnineand his empress

1395
01:23:17.830 --> 01:23:20.770
beg at the gates likeTarquin and his queen.

1396
01:23:22.070 --> 01:23:25.930
Now will I to the Goths,and raise a power

1397
01:23:25.930 --> 01:23:29.770
to be revenged on Rome andSaturnine.

1398
01:23:53.330 --> 01:23:56.130
So so, now sit.

1399
01:24:13.470 --> 01:24:14.870
And look you eat no more

1400
01:24:14.870 --> 01:24:17.370
than will preserve just somuch strength in us

1401
01:24:17.370 --> 01:24:20.500
as will revenge thesebitter woes of ours.

1402
01:24:20.500 --> 01:24:23.270
Marcus, unknit thatsorrow-wreathen knot.

1403
01:24:23.270 --> 01:24:25.800
Thy niece and I, poorcreatures, want our hands

1404
01:24:25.800 --> 01:24:29.530
and cannot passionate ourtenfold grief with foldedarms.

1405
01:24:29.530 --> 01:24:32.070
This poor right hand ofmine is left to tyrannize

1406
01:24:32.070 --> 01:24:34.600
upon my breast, who, whenmy heart,

1407
01:24:34.600 --> 01:24:37.030
all mad with misery, beatsin the hollow prison

1408
01:24:37.030 --> 01:24:39.730
of this flesh, then thus Ithump it down.

1409
01:24:43.100 --> 01:24:46.870
Thou map of woe that thusmust talk in signs.

1410
01:24:46.870 --> 01:24:50.070
When thy poor heart beatswith outrageous beating,

1411
01:24:50.070 --> 01:24:53.470
thou canst not strike itthus to make it still.

1412
01:24:54.800 --> 01:24:58.730
Wound it with sighing,girl; kill it with groans,

1413
01:24:58.730 --> 01:25:00.700
or get some little knifebetween thy teeth

1414
01:25:00.700 --> 01:25:03.430
and just against thouheart make thou a hole,

1415
01:25:03.430 --> 01:25:06.570
that all the tears thatthy poor eyes let fall

1416
01:25:06.570 --> 01:25:08.800
may run into that sinkand, soaking in,

1417
01:25:08.800 --> 01:25:11.630
drown the lamenting foolin sea-salt tears.

1418
01:25:11.630 --> 01:25:13.300
Fie, brother, fie!

1419
01:25:13.300 --> 01:25:15.830
Teach her not thus to laysuch violent hands

1420
01:25:15.830 --> 01:25:17.470
upon her tender life.

1421
01:25:17.470 --> 01:25:20.500
How now; has sorrow madethee dote already?

1422
01:25:20.500 --> 01:25:23.000
Why, Marcus, no man shouldbe mad but I.

1423
01:25:23.000 --> 01:25:26.230
What violent hands can shelay on her life?

1424
01:25:27.000 --> 01:25:28.900
O, handle not the theme,to talk of hands,

1425
01:25:28.900 --> 01:25:31.430
lest we remember stillthat we have none.

1426
01:25:32.500 --> 01:25:35.900
Fie, fie, how franticallyI shape my talk,

1427
01:25:35.900 --> 01:25:38.700
as if we could forget wehave no hands

1428
01:25:38.700 --> 01:25:41.570
if Marcus did not name theword of hands.

1429
01:25:44.100 --> 01:25:46.300
Come, let's fall to.

1430
01:25:48.570 --> 01:25:53.430
Gentle girl, eat this.

1431
01:25:57.000 --> 01:25:58.430
Here is no drink.

1432
01:26:01.700 --> 01:26:04.830
Hark, Marcus, what shesays.

1433
01:26:04.830 --> 01:26:08.330
I can interpret all hermartyred signs.

1434
01:26:08.330 --> 01:26:11.000
She says she drinks noother drink but tears,

1435
01:26:11.000 --> 01:26:13.800
brewed with her sorrows,meshed upon her cheeks.

1436
01:26:13.800 --> 01:26:17.200
Speechless complainer, Iwill learn thy thought.

1437
01:26:17.200 --> 01:26:19.600
In thy dumb action will Ibe as perfect

1438
01:26:19.600 --> 01:26:22.000
as begging hermits attheir holy prayers.

1439
01:26:22.000 --> 01:26:25.270
Thou shalt not sigh, norhold thy stumps to heaven,

1440
01:26:25.270 --> 01:26:28.800
nor wink, nor nod, norkneel, nor make a sign,

1441
01:26:28.800 --> 01:26:31.200
but I of these will wrestan alphabet

1442
01:26:31.200 --> 01:26:34.400
and by still practicelearn to know thy meaning.

1443
01:26:35.070 --> 01:26:38.270
Good grandsire, leavethese bitter deep laments.

1444
01:26:38.270 --> 01:26:40.930
Make my aunt merry withsome pleasing tale.

1445
01:26:42.100 --> 01:26:44.630
Alas, the tender boy, inpassion moved,

1446
01:26:44.630 --> 01:26:47.870
doth weep to see hisgrandsire's heaviness.

1447
01:26:54.300 --> 01:26:55.970
Peace, tender sapling.

1448
01:26:55.970 --> 01:26:57.730
Thou art made of tears,

1449
01:26:57.730 --> 01:27:00.800
and tears will quicklymelt thy life away.

1450
01:27:00.800 --> 01:27:03.000
What dost thou strike at,Marcus, with thy knife?

1451
01:27:03.000 --> 01:27:05.630
At that that I havekilled, my lorda fly.

1452
01:27:05.630 --> 01:27:09.700
Out on thee, murderer;thou kill'st my heart!

1453
01:27:09.700 --> 01:27:12.430
Mine eyes are cloyed withview of tyranny.

1454
01:27:12.430 --> 01:27:14.330
A deed of death done onthe innocent

1455
01:27:14.330 --> 01:27:15.570
becomes not Titus'brother.

1456
01:27:15.570 --> 01:27:16.670
Get thee gone.

1457
01:27:16.670 --> 01:27:18.230
I see thou art not for mycompany.

1458
01:27:18.230 --> 01:27:20.800
Alas, my lord, I have butkilled a fly.

1459
01:27:20.800 --> 01:27:26.400
But how if that fly had afather and mother?

1460
01:27:28.500 --> 01:27:31.670
How would he hang hisslender gilded wings

1461
01:27:31.670 --> 01:27:33.600
and buzz lamenting doingsin the air.

1462
01:27:33.600 --> 01:27:36.670
Poor harmless fly thatwith his pretty buzzingmelody

1463
01:27:36.670 --> 01:27:40.730
came here to make usmerry, and thou hastkilled him.

1464
01:27:41.870 --> 01:27:45.100
O, pardon, sir; it was ablack, ill-favored fly,

1465
01:27:45.100 --> 01:27:48.570
like to the empress' Moor;therefore I killed him.

1466
01:27:55.170 --> 01:27:59.500
O, then pardon me forreprehending thee,

1467
01:27:59.500 --> 01:28:01.830
for thou hast done acharitable deed.

1468
01:28:01.830 --> 01:28:04.730
Give me thy knife; I willinsult on him,

1469
01:28:04.730 --> 01:28:06.730
flattering myself as if itwere the Moor

1470
01:28:06.730 --> 01:28:08.570
come hither purposely topoison me.

1471
01:28:08.570 --> 01:28:11.230
There's for thyself, andthat's for Tamora.

1472
01:28:11.230 --> 01:28:13.000
Ah, sirrah!

1473
01:28:22.400 --> 01:28:24.370
Yet, I think, we are notbrought so low

1474
01:28:24.370 --> 01:28:26.370
but that between us we cankill a fly

1475
01:28:26.370 --> 01:28:29.630
that comes in likeness ofa coal-black Moor.

1476
01:28:30.970 --> 01:28:33.400
Alas, poor man; grief hasso wrought on him,

1477
01:28:33.400 --> 01:28:36.500
he takes false shadows fortrue substances.

1478
01:28:43.000 --> 01:28:44.200
Come, take away.

1479
01:28:47.070 --> 01:28:49.100
Lavinia, go with me.

1480
01:28:49.100 --> 01:28:51.400
I'll to thy closet and goread with thee

1481
01:28:51.400 --> 01:28:54.330
sad stories chanced in thetimes of old.

1482
01:28:56.370 --> 01:28:58.900
Come, boy, and go with me.

1483
01:29:07.130 --> 01:29:08.970
Thy sight is young,

1484
01:29:08.970 --> 01:29:14.770
and thou shalt read whenmine begin to dazzle.

1485
01:29:52.970 --> 01:29:55.000
Help, Grandsire, help!

1486
01:29:55.000 --> 01:29:56.670
My aunt Lavinia follows meeverywhere.

1487
01:29:56.670 --> 01:29:58.400
I know not why.

1488
01:29:58.400 --> 01:30:01.370
Good uncle Marcus, see howswift she comes.

1489
01:30:01.370 --> 01:30:03.570
Alas, sweet aunt, I knownot what you mean.

1490
01:30:03.570 --> 01:30:04.670
Stand by me, Lucius.

1491
01:30:04.670 --> 01:30:05.900
Do not fear thine aunt.

1492
01:30:05.900 --> 01:30:07.800
She loves thee, boy, toowell to do thee harm.

1493
01:30:07.800 --> 01:30:10.630
Ay, when my father was inRome, she did.

1494
01:30:10.630 --> 01:30:12.670
What means my nieceLavinia by these signs?

1495
01:30:12.670 --> 01:30:15.330
Fear her not, Lucius;somewhat does she mean.

1496
01:30:15.970 --> 01:30:19.100
See, Lucius, see how muchshe makes of thee.

1497
01:30:19.100 --> 01:30:20.900
Somewhither would she havethee go with her.

1498
01:30:20.900 --> 01:30:23.130
Ah, boy, Cornelia neverwith more care

1499
01:30:23.130 --> 01:30:25.570
read to her sons than shehath read to thee

1500
01:30:25.570 --> 01:30:28.100
sweet poetry and Tully'sorator.

1501
01:30:28.100 --> 01:30:30.970
Canst thou not guesswherefore she plies theethus?

1502
01:30:30.970 --> 01:30:33.800
My lord, I know not, I,nor can I guess,

1503
01:30:33.800 --> 01:30:35.930
unless some fit or frenzydo possess her.

1504
01:30:35.930 --> 01:30:38.630
For I have heard mygrandsire say full oft

1505
01:30:38.630 --> 01:30:41.100
extremities of grief wouldmake men mad.

1506
01:30:41.100 --> 01:30:44.030
And I have read thatHecuba of Troy ran madfor sorrow.

1507
01:30:44.030 --> 01:30:45.900
That made me to fear.

1508
01:30:45.900 --> 01:30:48.100
Although, my lord, I knowmy noble aunt

1509
01:30:48.100 --> 01:30:50.000
loves me as dear as e'ermy mother did

1510
01:30:50.000 --> 01:30:52.700
and would not but in furyfright my youth,

1511
01:30:52.700 --> 01:30:55.270
which made me down tothrow my books and fly

1512
01:30:55.270 --> 01:30:56.670
causeless, perhaps.

1513
01:30:56.670 --> 01:30:58.570
But pardon me, sweet aunt.

1514
01:30:58.570 --> 01:31:00.870
And, madam, if my uncleMarcus go,

1515
01:31:00.870 --> 01:31:03.030
I will most willinglyattend your ladyship.

1516
01:31:03.030 --> 01:31:04.130
Lucius, I will.

1517
01:31:08.870 --> 01:31:10.600
How now, Lavinia.

1518
01:31:10.600 --> 01:31:14.070
Marcus, what means this?

1519
01:31:14.070 --> 01:31:16.470
Some book there is thatshe desires to see.

1520
01:31:16.470 --> 01:31:18.370
Which is it, girl, ofthese?

1521
01:31:18.370 --> 01:31:19.530
Open them, boy.

1522
01:31:19.530 --> 01:31:22.530
But thou art deeper readand better skilled.

1523
01:31:22.530 --> 01:31:24.870
Come and take choice ofall my library,

1524
01:31:24.870 --> 01:31:27.400
and so beguile thy sorrow,till the heavens reveal

1525
01:31:27.400 --> 01:31:29.870
the damned contriver ofthis deed.

1526
01:31:30.800 --> 01:31:34.730
Why lifts she up her armsin sequence thus?

1527
01:31:34.730 --> 01:31:36.470
I think she means thatthere were

1528
01:31:36.470 --> 01:31:39.500
more than one confederatein the fact.

1529
01:31:39.500 --> 01:31:40.770
Ay, more there was;

1530
01:31:40.770 --> 01:31:42.770
or else to heaven sheheaves them for revenge.

1531
01:31:42.770 --> 01:31:46.830
Lucius, what book is thatshe tosseth so?

1532
01:31:46.830 --> 01:31:49.430
Grandsire, 'tis Ovid's"Metamorphoses."

1533
01:31:49.430 --> 01:31:50.730
My mother gave it me.

1534
01:31:50.730 --> 01:31:51.830
For love of her that'sgone,

1535
01:31:51.830 --> 01:31:53.500
perhaps she culled it fromamong the rest.

1536
01:31:53.500 --> 01:31:54.730
Soft.

1537
01:31:54.730 --> 01:31:57.270
So busily she turns theleaves.

1538
01:31:57.270 --> 01:31:59.030
What would she find?

1539
01:31:59.030 --> 01:32:01.170
Help her.

1540
01:32:01.170 --> 01:32:03.530
Lavinia, shall I read?

1541
01:32:10.030 --> 01:32:12.200
This is the tragic tale ofPhilomel

1542
01:32:12.200 --> 01:32:18.470
and treats of Tereus'treason and his rape.

1543
01:32:20.930 --> 01:32:24.430
And rape, I fear, was rootof thy annoy.

1544
01:32:25.800 --> 01:32:27.930
See, brother, see.

1545
01:32:27.930 --> 01:32:29.700
Note how she quotes theleaves.

1546
01:32:29.700 --> 01:32:32.600
Lavinia, were thou thussurprised, sweet girl,

1547
01:32:32.600 --> 01:32:35.200
ravished and wronged asPhilomela was,

1548
01:32:35.200 --> 01:32:38.800
forced in the vast andruthless, gloomy woods?

1549
01:32:40.000 --> 01:32:43.330
Ay, see, see.

1550
01:32:43.330 --> 01:32:45.630
Such a place there iswhere we did hunt

1551
01:32:45.630 --> 01:32:48.100
O, had we never, neverhunted there!

1552
01:32:48.100 --> 01:32:51.170
patterned by this the poethere describes,

1553
01:32:51.170 --> 01:32:55.630
by nature made for murdersand for rapes.

1554
01:32:55.630 --> 01:32:57.900
O, why should nature buildso foul a den,

1555
01:32:57.900 --> 01:33:01.430
unless the gods delight intragedies?

1556
01:33:01.430 --> 01:33:05.470
Give signs, sweet girl, forhere are none but friends,

1557
01:33:05.470 --> 01:33:08.330
what Roman lord it wasdurst do the deed.

1558
01:33:08.330 --> 01:33:11.500
Or slunk not Saturnine, asTarquin erst,

1559
01:33:11.500 --> 01:33:13.900
that left the camp to sinin Lucrece' bed?

1560
01:33:15.900 --> 01:33:18.170
Sit down, sweet niece.

1561
01:33:18.170 --> 01:33:20.330
Brother, sit down with me.

1562
01:33:26.330 --> 01:33:29.900
Apollo, Pallas, Jove, andMercury,

1563
01:33:29.900 --> 01:33:33.330
inspire me, that I maythis treason find.

1564
01:33:40.830 --> 01:33:44.300
My lord, look here.

1565
01:33:46.470 --> 01:33:49.470
Look here, Lavinia.

1566
01:33:49.470 --> 01:33:52.330
This sandy plot is plain.

1567
01:33:52.330 --> 01:33:59.800
Guide, if thou canst, thisafter me.

1568
01:34:00.600 --> 01:34:02.000
I have writ my name

1569
01:34:02.000 --> 01:34:05.670
without the help of anyhand at all.

1570
01:34:05.670 --> 01:34:09.630
Cursed be the heart thatforced us to this shift.

1571
01:34:09.630 --> 01:34:13.870
Write thou, good niece,and here display at last

1572
01:34:13.870 --> 01:34:17.600
what God will havediscovered for revenge.

1573
01:34:17.600 --> 01:34:23.370
Heaven guide thy pen toprint thy sorrows plain,

1574
01:34:23.370 --> 01:34:27.500
that we may know thetraitors and the truth.

1575
01:35:40.800 --> 01:35:43.400
Do you read, my lord, whatshe hath writ?

1576
01:35:56.730 --> 01:36:00.370
"Rape."

1577
01:36:00.370 --> 01:36:01.870
"Chiron."

1578
01:36:01.870 --> 01:36:04.970
"Demetrius."

1579
01:36:04.970 --> 01:36:12.030
Magni Dominator poli, Tamlentus audis scelera?

1580
01:36:12.030 --> 01:36:13.930
Tam lentus vides?

1581
01:36:13.930 --> 01:36:16.400
O, calm thee, gentle lord,

1582
01:36:16.400 --> 01:36:19.530
although I know there isenough written upon this earth

1583
01:36:19.530 --> 01:36:21.870
to stir a mutiny in themildest thoughts

1584
01:36:21.870 --> 01:36:25.130
and arm the minds ofinfants to exclaims.

1585
01:36:25.130 --> 01:36:28.130
Kneel down with me.

1586
01:36:28.130 --> 01:36:29.700
Lavinia, kneel.

1587
01:36:29.700 --> 01:36:33.870
And kneel, sweet boy, theRoman Hector's hope

1588
01:36:33.870 --> 01:36:37.500
and swear with me  as withthe woeful fere

1589
01:36:37.500 --> 01:36:39.400
and father of that chaste,dishonored dame,

1590
01:36:39.400 --> 01:36:41.930
Lord Junius Brutus swarefor Lucrece's rape

1591
01:36:41.930 --> 01:36:44.100
that we will prosecute bygood advice

1592
01:36:44.100 --> 01:36:46.430
mortal revenge upon thesetraitorous Goths

1593
01:36:46.430 --> 01:36:50.400
and see their blood or diewith this reproach.

1594
01:36:52.100 --> 01:36:59.770
'Tis sure enough, and youknew how.

1595
01:36:59.770 --> 01:37:04.430
But if you hunt thesebear-whelps, then beware.

1596
01:37:04.430 --> 01:37:08.700
The dam will wake; and ifshe wind ye once,

1597
01:37:08.700 --> 01:37:12.630
she's with the lion deeplystill in league

1598
01:37:12.630 --> 01:37:15.830
and lulls him while sheplayeth on her back.

1599
01:37:15.830 --> 01:37:20.400
And when he sleeps willshe do what she list.

1600
01:37:21.830 --> 01:37:25.870
You are a young huntsman,Marcus; let alone.

1601
01:37:25.870 --> 01:37:27.200
Come.

1602
01:37:27.200 --> 01:37:31.630
I will go get a leaf of brassand with a gad of steel

1603
01:37:31.630 --> 01:37:35.670
will write these words andlay it by.

1604
01:37:35.670 --> 01:37:40.530
The angry northern windwill blow these sands

1605
01:37:40.530 --> 01:37:42.130
like Sibyl's leavesabroad.

1606
01:37:42.130 --> 01:37:44.470
And where's our lessonthen?

1607
01:37:44.470 --> 01:37:45.870
Boy, what say you?

1608
01:37:45.870 --> 01:37:48.370
I say, my lord, that if Iwere a man,

1609
01:37:48.370 --> 01:37:50.400
their mother's bedchambershould not be safe

1610
01:37:50.400 --> 01:37:53.000
for these base bondmen tothe yoke of Rome.

1611
01:37:53.000 --> 01:37:54.200
Ay, there's my boy.

1612
01:37:54.200 --> 01:37:55.570
Thy father hath full oft

1613
01:37:55.570 --> 01:37:57.470
for his ungrateful countrydone the like.

1614
01:37:57.470 --> 01:38:00.100
And, uncle, so will I, andif I live.

1615
01:38:00.100 --> 01:38:01.770
Come, go with me into minearmory.

1616
01:38:01.770 --> 01:38:04.270
Lucius, I'll fit thee, andmy boy withal

1617
01:38:04.270 --> 01:38:06.830
shall carry from me to theempress' sons

1618
01:38:06.830 --> 01:38:10.070
presents that I intend tosend them both.

1619
01:38:10.070 --> 01:38:12.470
Come, come; thou'lt do mymessage, wilt thou not?

1620
01:38:12.470 --> 01:38:15.030
Ay, and with my dagger intheir bosoms, Grandsire.

1621
01:38:15.030 --> 01:38:18.030
No, boy, not so.

1622
01:38:18.030 --> 01:38:20.670
I'll teach thee anothercourse.

1623
01:38:22.470 --> 01:38:24.300
Lavinia, come.

1624
01:38:24.300 --> 01:38:26.270
Marcus, look to my house.

1625
01:38:26.270 --> 01:38:29.930
Lucius and I'll go braveit at the court.

1626
01:38:29.930 --> 01:38:33.070
Ay, marry, will we, sir,and we'll be waited on.

1627
01:38:35.530 --> 01:38:38.000
O, heavens, can you hear agood man groan

1628
01:38:38.000 --> 01:38:40.500
and not relent and notcompassion him?

1629
01:38:40.500 --> 01:38:43.170
Marcus, attend him in hisecstasy

1630
01:38:43.170 --> 01:38:46.770
that hath more scars ofsorrow in his heart

1631
01:38:46.770 --> 01:38:49.230
than foemen's marks uponhis battered shield,

1632
01:38:49.230 --> 01:38:53.400
and yet so just that hewill not revenge.

1633
01:38:53.400 --> 01:38:56.730
Revenge the heavens forold Andronicus.

1634
01:39:22.800 --> 01:39:25.900
Demetrius, here's the sonof Lucius.

1635
01:39:25.900 --> 01:39:27.630
He hath some message todeliver us.

1636
01:39:27.630 --> 01:39:31.370
Ay, some mad message fromhis mad grandfather.

1637
01:39:31.370 --> 01:39:33.630
My lords, with all thehumbleness I may,

1638
01:39:33.630 --> 01:39:35.600
I greet your honors fromAndronicus

1639
01:39:35.600 --> 01:39:38.670
and pray the Roman godsconfound you both.

1640
01:39:38.670 --> 01:39:41.130
Gramercy, lovely Lucius.

1641
01:39:42.430 --> 01:39:43.770
What's the news?

1642
01:39:43.770 --> 01:39:45.900
That you are bothdeciphered that's the news

1643
01:39:45.900 --> 01:39:48.200
for villains marked withrape.

1644
01:39:48.200 --> 01:39:50.200
May it please you, mygrandsire,

1645
01:39:50.200 --> 01:39:52.100
well advised, hath sent byme

1646
01:39:52.100 --> 01:39:53.830
the goodliest weapons ofhis armory

1647
01:39:53.830 --> 01:39:55.700
to gratify your honorableyouth,

1648
01:39:55.700 --> 01:39:58.330
the hope of Rome, for sohe bid me say.

1649
01:39:58.330 --> 01:40:00.870
And so I do, and with hisgifts present

1650
01:40:00.870 --> 01:40:02.700
Your Lordships, thatwhenever you have need,

1651
01:40:02.700 --> 01:40:04.670
you may be armed andappointed well.

1652
01:40:04.670 --> 01:40:08.270
And so I leave you both...

1653
01:40:08.270 --> 01:40:09.630
like bloody villains.

1654
01:40:09.630 --> 01:40:11.200
What's here?

1655
01:40:11.200 --> 01:40:15.270
A scroll, and writtenround about.

1656
01:40:15.270 --> 01:40:17.400
Let's see.

1657
01:40:17.400 --> 01:40:24.500
"Integer vitae,scelerisque purus,

1658
01:40:24.500 --> 01:40:33.230
non eget Mauri iaculis,nec arcu."

1659
01:40:33.230 --> 01:40:35.400
O, 'tis a verse in Horace.

1660
01:40:35.400 --> 01:40:36.600
I know it well.

1661
01:40:36.600 --> 01:40:38.600
I read it in the grammarlong ago.

1662
01:40:38.600 --> 01:40:41.670
Ay, just  A verse inHorace.

1663
01:40:41.670 --> 01:40:43.370
Right, you have it.

1664
01:40:45.500 --> 01:40:48.600
Now, what a thing it is tobe an ass.

1665
01:40:48.600 --> 01:40:51.170
Here's no sound jest.

1666
01:40:51.170 --> 01:40:53.370
The old man hath foundtheir guilt

1667
01:40:53.370 --> 01:40:56.130
and sends them weaponswrapped about with lines

1668
01:40:56.130 --> 01:40:59.000
that wound, beyond theirfeeling, to the quick.

1669
01:40:59.000 --> 01:41:01.800
But were our witty empresswell afoot,

1670
01:41:01.800 --> 01:41:05.000
she would applaudAndronicus' conceit.

1671
01:41:05.000 --> 01:41:09.070
But let her rest in herunrest awhile.

1672
01:41:09.070 --> 01:41:14.230
And now, young lords,was't not a happy star

1673
01:41:14.230 --> 01:41:16.200
led us to Rome, strangers,

1674
01:41:16.200 --> 01:41:17.970
and more than so captives

1675
01:41:17.970 --> 01:41:19.700
to be advanced to thisheight?

1676
01:41:19.700 --> 01:41:22.300
It doth me good to see sogreat a lord

1677
01:41:22.300 --> 01:41:25.570
basely insinuate and sendus gifts.

1678
01:41:26.600 --> 01:41:29.130
Had he not reason, LordDemetrius?

1679
01:41:29.130 --> 01:41:32.100
Did you not use hisdaughter very friendly?

1680
01:41:32.100 --> 01:41:34.870
I would we had a thousandRoman dames

1681
01:41:34.870 --> 01:41:38.500
at such a bay, by turn toserve our lust.

1682
01:41:38.500 --> 01:41:40.200
A charitable wish, andfull of love.

1683
01:41:40.200 --> 01:41:42.630
Here lacks but your motherfor to say amen.

1684
01:41:42.630 --> 01:41:44.470
And would she for twentythousand more.

1685
01:41:44.470 --> 01:41:48.200
Come, let us go and prayto all the gods

1686
01:41:48.200 --> 01:41:50.400
for our beloved mother inher pains.

1687
01:41:50.400 --> 01:41:53.170
Pray to the devils; thegods have given us over.

1688
01:41:54.900 --> 01:41:57.430
Why do the emperor'strumpets flourish thus?

1689
01:41:57.430 --> 01:41:59.400
Belike, for joy theemperor hath a son.

1690
01:41:59.400 --> 01:42:03.070
Soft. Who comes here?

1691
01:42:03.070 --> 01:42:05.930
O, tell me, did you seeAaron the Moor?

1692
01:42:05.930 --> 01:42:09.470
Well, more or less, orne'er a whit at all,

1693
01:42:09.470 --> 01:42:12.170
here Aaron is; and whatwith Aaron now?

1694
01:42:12.170 --> 01:42:15.600
O, gentle Aaron, we areall undone.

1695
01:42:15.600 --> 01:42:18.830
Now help, or woe betidethee evermore.

1696
01:42:18.830 --> 01:42:20.630
Why, what a caterwaulingdost thou keep.

1697
01:42:20.630 --> 01:42:22.670
What dost thou wrap andfumble in thy arms?

1698
01:42:22.670 --> 01:42:25.600
O, that which I would hidefrom heaven's eye.

1699
01:42:25.600 --> 01:42:30.370
Our empress' shame andstately Rome's disgrace.

1700
01:42:30.370 --> 01:42:33.170
She is delivered, lords;she is delivered.

1701
01:42:33.170 --> 01:42:34.500
To whom?

1702
01:42:34.500 --> 01:42:36.500
I mean she is broughtabed.

1703
01:42:36.500 --> 01:42:37.700
Well, God give her goodrest.

1704
01:42:37.700 --> 01:42:38.800
What hath he sent her?

1705
01:42:38.800 --> 01:42:39.900
A devil.

1706
01:42:39.900 --> 01:42:42.500
Why, then she is thedevil's dam;

1707
01:42:42.500 --> 01:42:43.830
a joyful issue.

1708
01:42:43.830 --> 01:42:48.570
A joyless, dismal, black,and sorrowful issue.

1709
01:42:48.570 --> 01:42:51.570
Here is the babe, asloathsome as a toad

1710
01:42:51.570 --> 01:42:54.570
amongst the fair-facedbreeders of our clime.

1711
01:42:54.570 --> 01:42:59.170
The empress sends it thee thy stamp, thy seal

1712
01:42:59.170 --> 01:43:03.370
and bids thee christen itwith thy dagger's point.

1713
01:43:03.370 --> 01:43:04.730
Zounds, ye whore!

1714
01:43:04.730 --> 01:43:07.800
Is black so base a hue?

1715
01:43:14.930 --> 01:43:18.430
Sweet blowse,

1716
01:43:18.430 --> 01:43:22.530
you are a beauteousblossom sure.

1717
01:43:22.530 --> 01:43:26.100
Villain, what hast thoudone?

1718
01:43:26.100 --> 01:43:28.270
That which thou canst notundo.

1719
01:43:28.270 --> 01:43:30.300
Thou hast undone ourmother.

1720
01:43:30.300 --> 01:43:33.400
Villain, I have done thymother.

1721
01:43:33.400 --> 01:43:35.870
And therein, hellish dog,hast thou undone her.

1722
01:43:37.600 --> 01:43:39.870
Woe to her chance,

1723
01:43:39.870 --> 01:43:42.230
Damned her loathed choice.

1724
01:43:42.230 --> 01:43:45.630
Accursed the offspring ofso foul a fiend.

1725
01:43:45.630 --> 01:43:46.800
It shall not live.

1726
01:43:46.800 --> 01:43:47.900
It shall not die.

1727
01:43:47.900 --> 01:43:51.100
Aaron, it must; the motherwills it so.

1728
01:43:51.100 --> 01:43:52.630
What, must it, nurse?

1729
01:43:52.630 --> 01:43:55.670
Then let no man but I doexecution

1730
01:43:55.670 --> 01:43:56.970
on my flesh and blood.

1731
01:43:56.970 --> 01:43:59.130
I'll broach the tadpole onmy rapier's point.

1732
01:43:59.130 --> 01:44:01.330
Nurse, give it to me!

1733
01:44:01.330 --> 01:44:03.130
My sword shall soondispatch it.

1734
01:44:03.130 --> 01:44:06.430
Sooner this sword shallplough thy bowels up!

1735
01:44:06.430 --> 01:44:10.670
Stay, murderous villains;will you kill your brother!

1736
01:44:10.670 --> 01:44:12.930
Now, by the burning tapersof the sky

1737
01:44:12.930 --> 01:44:15.830
that shone so brightlywhen this boy was got,

1738
01:44:15.830 --> 01:44:18.700
he dies upon my scimitar'ssharp point

1739
01:44:18.700 --> 01:44:22.230
that touches this, myfirst-born son and heir.

1740
01:44:22.230 --> 01:44:25.500
I tell you, younglings,not Enceladus,

1741
01:44:25.500 --> 01:44:29.300
with all his threateningband of Typhon's brood,

1742
01:44:29.300 --> 01:44:32.770
nor great Alcides, nor thegod of war,

1743
01:44:32.770 --> 01:44:35.700
shall seize this prey outof his father's hands.

1744
01:44:41.600 --> 01:44:47.770
What, what, ye sanguine,shallow-hearted boys

1745
01:44:47.770 --> 01:44:52.630
ye white-limed walls, yealehouse painted signs!

1746
01:44:52.630 --> 01:44:55.330
Coal-black is better thananother hue

