01:44:55.330 --> 01:44:58.070
in that it scorns to bearanother hue.

1748
01:44:58.070 --> 01:45:00.730
For all the water in theocean

1749
01:45:00.730 --> 01:45:03.800
can never turn the swan'sblack legs to white,

1750
01:45:03.800 --> 01:45:06.470
although she lave themhourly in the flood.

1751
01:45:13.130 --> 01:45:17.700
Tell the empress from me, Iam of age to keep mine own;

1752
01:45:17.700 --> 01:45:19.570
excuse it how she can.

1753
01:45:20.730 --> 01:45:23.730
Wilt thou betray thy noblemistress thus?

1754
01:45:23.730 --> 01:45:28.830
My mistress is mymistress, this my self

1755
01:45:28.830 --> 01:45:32.200
the vigor and the pictureof my youth.

1756
01:45:32.200 --> 01:45:36.770
This before all the worlddo I prefer.

1757
01:45:36.770 --> 01:45:42.370
This maugre all the worldwill I keep safe,

1758
01:45:42.370 --> 01:45:45.170
or some of you shall smokefor it in Rome.

1759
01:45:45.170 --> 01:45:48.430
By this our mother is forever shamed.

1760
01:45:48.430 --> 01:45:51.430
Rome will despise her forthis foul escape.

1761
01:45:51.430 --> 01:45:54.200
The emperor in his ragewill doom her death.

1762
01:45:54.200 --> 01:45:56.700
I blush to think upon thisignomy.

1763
01:45:56.700 --> 01:46:00.070
Why, there's the privilegeyour beauty bears.

1764
01:46:00.070 --> 01:46:03.170
Fie, treacherous hue, thatwill betray with blushing

1765
01:46:03.170 --> 01:46:07.230
the close enacts andcounsels of thy heart.

1766
01:46:07.230 --> 01:46:10.100
Here's a young lad framedof another leer.

1767
01:46:10.100 --> 01:46:14.370
Look how the black slavesmiles upon the father,

1768
01:46:14.370 --> 01:46:17.830
as who should say, "Oldlad, I am thine own."

1769
01:46:19.270 --> 01:46:22.400
He is your brother, lords,sensibly fed

1770
01:46:22.400 --> 01:46:25.130
of that self-blood thatfirst gave life to you;

1771
01:46:25.130 --> 01:46:27.630
and from your womb whereyou imprisoned were,

1772
01:46:27.630 --> 01:46:29.930
he is enfranchised andbrought to light.

1773
01:46:29.930 --> 01:46:33.170
Nay, he is your brother bythe surer side,

1774
01:46:33.170 --> 01:46:36.430
although my seal bestamped in his face.

1775
01:46:36.430 --> 01:46:40.500
Aaron, what shall I sayunto the empress?

1776
01:46:46.100 --> 01:46:48.930
Advise thee, Aaron, whatis to be done,

1777
01:46:48.930 --> 01:46:52.030
and we will all subscribeto thy advice.

1778
01:46:53.430 --> 01:46:56.370
Save thou the child, so wemay all be safe.

1779
01:46:56.370 --> 01:47:00.170
Then sit we down and letus all consult.

1780
01:47:00.170 --> 01:47:03.000
My son and I will have thewind of you.

1781
01:47:03.000 --> 01:47:05.000
Keep there.

1782
01:47:10.400 --> 01:47:14.800
Now talk at pleasure ofyour safety.

1783
01:47:19.030 --> 01:47:21.470
How many women saw thischild of his?

1784
01:47:21.470 --> 01:47:24.070
Why, so, brave lords

1785
01:47:24.070 --> 01:47:27.500
When we join in league, Iam a lamb.

1786
01:47:27.500 --> 01:47:29.530
But if you brave the Moor,

1787
01:47:29.530 --> 01:47:32.230
the chafed boar, themountain lioness,

1788
01:47:32.230 --> 01:47:36.230
the ocean swells not so asAaron storms.

1789
01:47:36.230 --> 01:47:40.430
But say again, how manysaw the child?

1790
01:47:40.430 --> 01:47:43.500
Cornelia the midwife andmyself,

1791
01:47:43.500 --> 01:47:45.770
and no one else but thedelivered empress.

1792
01:47:45.770 --> 01:47:49.130
The empress, the midwife,and yourself.

1793
01:47:49.130 --> 01:47:52.170
Two may keep counsel whenthe third's away.

1794
01:47:54.930 --> 01:47:59.330
Go to the empress; tellher this I said.

1795
01:48:01.670 --> 01:48:05.400
Weeke, weeke!

1796
01:48:05.400 --> 01:48:07.830
So cries a pig prepared tothe spit.

1797
01:48:07.830 --> 01:48:10.100
What mean'st thou, Aaron?Wherefore didst thou this?

1798
01:48:10.100 --> 01:48:13.200
O, Lord, sir, 'tis a deedof policy.

1799
01:48:13.200 --> 01:48:15.870
Shall she live to betraythis guilt of ours,

1800
01:48:15.870 --> 01:48:17.630
a long-tongued babblinggossip?

1801
01:48:17.630 --> 01:48:19.030
No, lords, no.

1802
01:48:19.030 --> 01:48:21.870
And now be it known to youmy full intent.

1803
01:48:21.870 --> 01:48:23.970
Not far, one Muliteus, mycountryman.

1804
01:48:23.970 --> 01:48:26.070
His wife but yesternightwas brought to bed.

1805
01:48:26.070 --> 01:48:29.070
His child is like to her,fair as you are.

1806
01:48:29.070 --> 01:48:30.670
Go pack with him, give themother gold

1807
01:48:30.670 --> 01:48:32.770
and tell them both thecircumstance of all,

1808
01:48:32.770 --> 01:48:35.300
and how by this theirchild shall be advanced

1809
01:48:35.300 --> 01:48:38.070
and be received for theemperor's heir

1810
01:48:38.070 --> 01:48:40.030
and substituted in theplace of mine

1811
01:48:40.030 --> 01:48:42.730
to calm this tempestwhirling in the court;

1812
01:48:42.730 --> 01:48:45.400
and let the emperor dandlehim for his own.

1813
01:48:47.600 --> 01:48:49.400
Hark ye, lords.

1814
01:48:49.400 --> 01:48:52.500
You see I have given herphysic.

1815
01:48:52.500 --> 01:48:54.970
And you must needs bestowher funeral.

1816
01:48:54.970 --> 01:48:58.300
The fields are near, andyou are gallant grooms.

1817
01:48:58.300 --> 01:49:00.130
This done, see that youtake no longer days,

1818
01:49:00.130 --> 01:49:02.630
but send the midwife to mepresently.

1819
01:49:02.630 --> 01:49:04.800
The midwife and the nursewell made away,

1820
01:49:04.800 --> 01:49:08.500
then let the ladies tattlewhat they please.

1821
01:49:11.100 --> 01:49:15.900
Aaron, I see thou wilt nottrust the air with secrets.

1822
01:49:15.900 --> 01:49:17.930
For this care of Tamora,

1823
01:49:17.930 --> 01:49:21.500
herself and hers arehighly bound to thee.

1824
01:49:31.530 --> 01:49:34.500
Now to the Goths, as swiftas swallow flies,

1825
01:49:34.500 --> 01:49:37.400
there to dispose thistreasure in mine arms

1826
01:49:37.400 --> 01:49:39.830
and secretly to greet theempress' friends.

1827
01:49:39.830 --> 01:49:42.770
Come on, you thick-lippedslave.

1828
01:49:42.770 --> 01:49:44.270
I'll bear you hence;

1829
01:49:44.270 --> 01:49:47.370
for it is you that puts usto our shifts.

1830
01:49:47.370 --> 01:49:50.630
I'll make you feed onberries and on roots

1831
01:49:50.630 --> 01:49:53.630
and feed on curds and wheyand suck the goat

1832
01:49:53.630 --> 01:49:57.200
and cabin in a cave andbring you up

1833
01:49:57.200 --> 01:49:59.670
to be a warrior andcommand a camp.

1834
01:50:30.370 --> 01:50:32.070
Come, Marcus, come.

1835
01:50:32.070 --> 01:50:34.800
Kinsmen, this is the way.

1836
01:50:34.800 --> 01:50:37.600
Sir boy, let me see yourarchery.

1837
01:50:39.200 --> 01:50:42.100
Look you draw home enough,and 'tis there straight.

1838
01:50:57.270 --> 01:51:01.000
The goddess of justice hasleft the earth.

1839
01:51:01.000 --> 01:51:04.100
Be you remembered, Marcus:she's gone, she's fled.

1840
01:51:06.130 --> 01:51:09.800
Sirs, take you to yourtools.

1841
01:51:15.670 --> 01:51:16.830
You, cousins,

1842
01:51:16.830 --> 01:51:19.000
shall so sound the ocean,cast your nets.

1843
01:51:19.000 --> 01:51:21.470
Happily you may catch herin the sea.

1844
01:51:21.470 --> 01:51:24.370
Well, there's as littlejustice as at land.

1845
01:51:24.370 --> 01:51:27.130
No; Publius and Sempronius,you must do it.

1846
01:51:27.130 --> 01:51:29.900
'Tis you must dig; withmattock and with spade,

1847
01:51:29.900 --> 01:51:32.070
pierce the inmost centreof the earth.

1848
01:51:32.070 --> 01:51:33.600
Then, when you come toPluto's region,

1849
01:51:33.600 --> 01:51:35.500
I pray you, deliver himthis petition.

1850
01:51:35.500 --> 01:51:39.470
Tell him it is for justiceand for aid

1851
01:51:39.470 --> 01:51:41.700
and that it comes from oldAndronicus,

1852
01:51:41.700 --> 01:51:43.830
shaken with sorrows inungrateful Rome.

1853
01:51:47.700 --> 01:51:49.870
O, Rome.

1854
01:51:52.170 --> 01:51:55.500
Well, well, I made theemiserable

1855
01:51:55.500 --> 01:51:57.830
that time I threw thepeople's suffrages

1856
01:51:57.830 --> 01:52:01.100
on him that now dothtyrannize o'er me.

1857
01:52:06.300 --> 01:52:09.030
Go get you gone, and praybe careful all.

1858
01:52:09.030 --> 01:52:11.430
Leave you not oneman-of-war unsearched.

1859
01:52:11.430 --> 01:52:13.500
This wicked emperor mayhave shipped her hence;

1860
01:52:13.500 --> 01:52:16.330
then kinsmen, we may gopipe for justice.

1861
01:52:21.870 --> 01:52:23.970
Publius, is not this aheavy case,

1862
01:52:23.970 --> 01:52:26.000
to see thy noble unclethus distract?

1863
01:52:26.000 --> 01:52:28.300
Therefore, my lords, ithighly us concerns

1864
01:52:28.300 --> 01:52:30.730
by day and night to attendhim carefully

1865
01:52:30.730 --> 01:52:32.630
and feed his humor kindlyas we may

1866
01:52:32.630 --> 01:52:34.630
till time beget somecareful remedy.

1867
01:52:34.630 --> 01:52:37.500
My son, his sorrows arepast remedy.

1868
01:52:37.500 --> 01:52:39.770
Join with the Goths, andwith revengeful war

1869
01:52:39.770 --> 01:52:41.630
take wreak on Rome forthis ingratitude,

1870
01:52:41.630 --> 01:52:43.670
and vengeance on thetraitor Saturnine.

1871
01:52:43.670 --> 01:52:44.770
Publius, how now?

1872
01:52:44.770 --> 01:52:45.870
How now, my masters?

1873
01:52:45.870 --> 01:52:47.800
What, have you met withher?

1874
01:52:47.800 --> 01:52:50.230
No, my good lord. butPluto sends you word,

1875
01:52:50.230 --> 01:52:52.570
if you will have Revengein hell, you shall.

1876
01:52:52.570 --> 01:52:55.170
Marry, for Justice, she isso employed, he thinks,

1877
01:52:55.170 --> 01:52:57.030
with Jove in heaven, orsomewhere else,

1878
01:52:57.030 --> 01:52:59.230
so that perforce you mustneeds stay a time.

1879
01:52:59.230 --> 01:53:04.400
He doth me wrong to feedme with delays.

1880
01:53:04.400 --> 01:53:06.770
I'll dive into the burninglake below

1881
01:53:06.770 --> 01:53:11.000
and pull her out ofAcheron by the heels.

1882
01:53:17.200 --> 01:53:23.600
Marcus, we are but shrubs,no cedars we,

1883
01:53:23.600 --> 01:53:28.000
no big-boned men framed ofthe cyclops' size.

1884
01:53:30.400 --> 01:53:35.670
But metal, Marcus, steelto the very back,

1885
01:53:35.670 --> 01:53:39.130
yet wrung with wrongs morethan our backs can bear.

1886
01:53:39.130 --> 01:53:44.400
And, sith there is nojustice in earth or hell,

1887
01:53:44.400 --> 01:53:49.270
we will solicit heaven,move the gods

1888
01:53:49.270 --> 01:53:51.900
to send down justice forto wreak our wrongs.

1889
01:53:51.900 --> 01:53:53.730
Come, to this gear.

1890
01:53:53.730 --> 01:53:56.300
You are a good archer,Marcus.

1891
01:53:56.300 --> 01:53:58.870
"Ad Jovem " that's foryou.

1892
01:53:58.870 --> 01:54:01.070
Here "Ad Apollinem."

1893
01:54:01.070 --> 01:54:03.600
"Ad Martem " that's formyself.

1894
01:54:07.600 --> 01:54:09.570
Here, boy, "To Pallas."

1895
01:54:09.570 --> 01:54:11.530
Here "To Mercury."

1896
01:54:11.530 --> 01:54:14.900
"To Saturn," Caius  not toSaturnine.

1897
01:54:14.900 --> 01:54:17.830
You were as good to shootagainst the wind.

1898
01:54:22.300 --> 01:54:23.600
Come to it, boy.

1899
01:54:27.930 --> 01:54:31.300
Marcus, loose when I bid.

1900
01:54:31.300 --> 01:54:33.100
Of my word, I have writtento effect.

1901
01:54:33.100 --> 01:54:35.230
There's not a god leftunsolicited.

1902
01:54:35.230 --> 01:54:39.000
Kinsmen, shoot all yourshafts into the court.

1903
01:54:39.000 --> 01:54:41.330
We will afflict theemperor in his pride.

1904
01:54:52.930 --> 01:54:55.030
Now, masters,

1905
01:54:57.300 --> 01:54:59.100
draw.

1906
01:55:06.230 --> 01:55:09.030
Well done, Lucius!

1907
01:55:09.030 --> 01:55:10.670
My lord, I aimed a milebeyond the moon.

1908
01:55:10.670 --> 01:55:12.270
Your letter is withJupiter by this.

1909
01:55:12.270 --> 01:55:13.730
Why, there it goes.

1910
01:55:13.730 --> 01:55:16.830
God give his lordship joy.

1911
01:55:20.300 --> 01:55:24.770
News, news from heaven.

1912
01:55:24.770 --> 01:55:26.430
Marcus, the post is come.

1913
01:55:26.430 --> 01:55:27.570
Sirrah, what tidings?

1914
01:55:27.570 --> 01:55:28.730
Have you any letters?

1915
01:55:28.730 --> 01:55:29.830
Shall I have justice?

1916
01:55:29.830 --> 01:55:32.300
What says Jupiter?

1917
01:55:32.300 --> 01:55:34.830
Oh, the gibbet-maker?

1918
01:55:34.830 --> 01:55:37.930
He says that he hath takenthem down again,

1919
01:55:37.930 --> 01:55:40.570
for the man must not behanged till the next week.

1920
01:55:40.570 --> 01:55:43.500
But what says Jupiter, Iask thee?

1921
01:55:44.700 --> 01:55:47.570
Alas, sir, I know notJupiter.

1922
01:55:47.570 --> 01:55:49.870
I never drank with him inall my life.

1923
01:55:49.870 --> 01:55:52.300
Why, villain, art not thouthe carrier?

1924
01:55:52.300 --> 01:55:56.770
Ay, of my pigeons, sir;nothing else.

1925
01:55:58.700 --> 01:56:03.600
Why, didst thou not comefrom heaven?

1926
01:56:03.600 --> 01:56:05.370
From heaven?

1927
01:56:05.370 --> 01:56:09.200
Alas, sir, no, I nevercame there.

1928
01:56:09.200 --> 01:56:11.070
God forbid I should be sobold

1929
01:56:11.070 --> 01:56:13.400
to press to heaven in myyoung days.

1930
01:56:13.400 --> 01:56:15.300
Why, I am going with mypigeons

1931
01:56:15.300 --> 01:56:17.970
to the Tribunal Plebs, totake up a matter

1932
01:56:17.970 --> 01:56:21.670
of brawl betwixt my uncle andone of the imperial's men.

1933
01:56:21.670 --> 01:56:23.630
Why, sir, this is as fitas can be

1934
01:56:23.630 --> 01:56:25.030
to serve you for youroration.

1935
01:56:25.030 --> 01:56:28.530
Let him deliver the pigeons tothe emperor from you.

1936
01:56:28.530 --> 01:56:32.230
Can you deliver an orationto the emperor with a grace?

1937
01:56:32.230 --> 01:56:33.970
Nay, truly, sir.

1938
01:56:33.970 --> 01:56:36.500
I could never say grace inall my life.

1939
01:56:36.500 --> 01:56:37.970
Come hither, sirrah.

1940
01:56:42.130 --> 01:56:45.400
Make no more ado, but giveyour pigeons to the emperor.

1941
01:56:45.400 --> 01:56:48.630
By me thou shalt havejustice at his hands.

1942
01:56:48.630 --> 01:56:50.500
Hold, hold.

1943
01:56:50.500 --> 01:56:54.500
Here is money for yourcharges.

1944
01:56:55.370 --> 01:56:59.300
Sirrah, can you with a gracedeliver up a supplication?

1945
01:56:59.300 --> 01:57:00.930
Ay, sir.

1946
01:57:00.930 --> 01:57:03.970
Then here is asupplication for you.

1947
01:57:03.970 --> 01:57:05.200
And when you come to him,

1948
01:57:05.200 --> 01:57:07.770
at the first approach, youmust kneel,

1949
01:57:07.770 --> 01:57:09.970
and then kiss his foot,

1950
01:57:09.970 --> 01:57:11.330
and then deliver up yourpigeons,

1951
01:57:11.330 --> 01:57:14.170
and then look for yourreward.

1952
01:57:14.170 --> 01:57:17.300
I'll be at hand, sir; seeyou do it bravely.

1953
01:57:17.300 --> 01:57:19.700
I warrant you, sir, Iwill.

1954
01:57:19.700 --> 01:57:22.300
Sirrah, hast thou a knife?

1955
01:57:22.300 --> 01:57:24.230
Ay, sir.

1956
01:57:24.230 --> 01:57:26.030
Well, let me see it.

1957
01:57:30.130 --> 01:57:34.130
Here, Marcus, fold it inthe oration;

1958
01:57:34.130 --> 01:57:36.370
for thou hast made it likean humble suppliant.

1959
01:57:40.000 --> 01:57:42.170
And when you have given itto the emperor,

1960
01:57:42.170 --> 01:57:45.630
knock at my door; tell mewhat he says.

1961
01:57:45.630 --> 01:57:48.030
God be with you, sir; Iwill.

1962
01:57:50.930 --> 01:57:52.100
Come, Marcus, come.

1963
01:57:52.100 --> 01:57:54.100
Publius, follow me.

1964
01:58:14.400 --> 01:58:17.630
Why, lords, what wrongsare these!

1965
01:58:19.700 --> 01:58:21.930
Was ever seen an emperorin Rome

1966
01:58:21.930 --> 01:58:26.230
thus overborne, troubled,confronted thus and,

1967
01:58:26.230 --> 01:58:31.270
for the extent of egal justice,used in such contempt?

1968
01:58:31.270 --> 01:58:34.830
My lords, you know, asknow the mightful gods,

1969
01:58:34.830 --> 01:58:36.430
however these disturbersof our peace

1970
01:58:36.430 --> 01:58:38.570
buzz in the people's ears,there nought hath passed

1971
01:58:38.570 --> 01:58:41.500
but even with law againstthe wilful sons

1972
01:58:41.500 --> 01:58:44.170
of old Andronicus.

1973
01:58:44.170 --> 01:58:47.700
And what and if hissorrows have sooverwhelmed his wits?

1974
01:58:47.700 --> 01:58:50.130
Shall we be thus afflictedin his wreaks,

1975
01:58:50.130 --> 01:58:54.070
his fits, his frenzy, andhis bitterness?

1976
01:58:54.070 --> 01:58:57.830
And now he writes toheaven for his redress.

1977
01:58:57.830 --> 01:59:02.030
See, here's "To Jove,"

1978
01:59:02.030 --> 01:59:04.170
and this "To Mercury."

1979
01:59:04.170 --> 01:59:07.070
This "To Apollo,"

1980
01:59:07.070 --> 01:59:11.170
this "To the God of War."

1981
01:59:11.170 --> 01:59:15.470
Sweet scrolls to fly aboutthe streets of Rome!

1982
01:59:15.470 --> 01:59:17.670
What's this but libellingagainst the Senate

1983
01:59:17.670 --> 01:59:20.600
and blazoning ourinjustice everywhere?

1984
01:59:22.170 --> 01:59:23.970
A goodly humor, is it not,my lords,

1985
01:59:23.970 --> 01:59:26.930
as who would say in Romeno justice were?

1986
01:59:26.930 --> 01:59:31.300
But if I live, his feignedecstasies

1987
01:59:31.300 --> 01:59:33.670
shall be no shelter tothese outrages;

1988
01:59:33.670 --> 01:59:36.600
but he and his shall knowthat justice lives

1989
01:59:36.600 --> 01:59:39.800
in Saturninus' health,whom, if she sleep,

1990
01:59:39.800 --> 01:59:42.230
he'll so awake as he infury

1991
01:59:42.230 --> 01:59:45.470
shall cut off the proudestconspirator that lives.

1992
01:59:53.700 --> 01:59:58.530
My gracious lord, mylovely Saturnine,

1993
01:59:58.530 --> 02:00:02.230
lord of my life, commanderof my thoughts,

1994
02:00:02.230 --> 02:00:06.800
calm thee, and bear thefaults of Titus' age,

1995
02:00:06.800 --> 02:00:09.500
the effects of sorrow forhis valiant sons

