02:00:09.500 --> 02:00:12.830
whose loss hath pierced himdeep and scarred his heart;

1997
02:00:12.830 --> 02:00:15.270
and rather comfort hisdistressed plight

1998
02:00:15.270 --> 02:00:18.530
than prosecute the meanest orthe best for these contempts.

1999
02:00:24.900 --> 02:00:28.800
Why, thus it shall becomehigh-witted Tamora

2000
02:00:28.800 --> 02:00:30.600
to gloze with all.

2001
02:00:30.600 --> 02:00:33.100
But Titus, I have touchedthee to the quick,

2002
02:00:33.100 --> 02:00:35.170
thy life-blood out.

2003
02:00:35.170 --> 02:00:38.900
If Aaron now be wise, thenall is safe,

2004
02:00:38.900 --> 02:00:42.570
the anchor in the port.

2005
02:00:42.570 --> 02:00:43.670
How now, good fellow.

2006
02:00:43.670 --> 02:00:45.030
Wouldst thou speak withus?

2007
02:00:45.030 --> 02:00:48.970
Yea, forsooth, and yourmistership be imperial.

2008
02:00:48.970 --> 02:00:52.070
Empress I am, but yondersits the emperor.

2009
02:00:54.700 --> 02:00:56.900
'Tis he.

2010
02:00:56.900 --> 02:01:00.430
God and Saint Stephen giveyou godden.

2011
02:01:00.430 --> 02:01:05.370
I have brought you aletter and a couple ofpigeons here.

2012
02:01:10.700 --> 02:01:13.370
Go take him away, and hanghim presently.

2013
02:01:13.370 --> 02:01:16.970
How much money must Ihave?

2014
02:01:16.970 --> 02:01:19.000
Come, sirrah; you must behanged.

2015
02:01:19.000 --> 02:01:21.830
Hanged by our lady?

2016
02:01:21.830 --> 02:01:27.930
Then I have brought up aneck to a fair end.

2017
02:01:27.930 --> 02:01:32.200
Despiteful and intolerablewrongs!

2018
02:01:32.200 --> 02:01:35.700
Shall I endure thismonstrous villainy?

2019
02:01:35.700 --> 02:01:38.800
I know from whence thissame device proceeds.

2020
02:01:38.800 --> 02:01:42.370
May this be borne  as ifhis traitorous sons

2021
02:01:42.370 --> 02:01:44.730
that died by law formurder of our brother

2022
02:01:44.730 --> 02:01:46.870
have by my means beenbutchered wrongfully?

2023
02:01:46.870 --> 02:01:49.170
Go drag the villain hitherby the hair.

2024
02:01:49.170 --> 02:01:53.170
Nor age nor honor shallshape privilege.

2025
02:01:53.170 --> 02:01:56.730
For this proud mock, I'llbe thy slaughterman,

2026
02:01:56.730 --> 02:02:00.370
sly frantic wretch, thatholp'st to make me great,

2027
02:02:00.370 --> 02:02:03.600
in hope thyself shouldgovern Rome and me.

2028
02:02:03.600 --> 02:02:05.630
What news with thee,Aemilius?

2029
02:02:05.630 --> 02:02:07.430
Arm, my lords!

2030
02:02:07.430 --> 02:02:09.600
Rome never had more cause.

2031
02:02:09.600 --> 02:02:11.600
The Goths have gatheredhead,

2032
02:02:11.600 --> 02:02:14.300
and with a power of highresolved men bent to the spoil,

2033
02:02:14.300 --> 02:02:16.700
they hither march amain,under conduct of Lucius,

2034
02:02:16.700 --> 02:02:20.700
son to old Andronicus, whothreats in course of hisrevenge

2035
02:02:20.700 --> 02:02:23.470
to do as much as everCoriolanus did.

2036
02:02:23.470 --> 02:02:29.170
Is warlike Lucius generalof the Goths?

2037
02:02:29.170 --> 02:02:33.030
These tidings nip me, andI hang the head

2038
02:02:33.030 --> 02:02:40.070
as flowers with frost, orgrass beat down withstorms.

2039
02:02:40.070 --> 02:02:47.530
Ay, now begins our sorrowsto approach.

2040
02:02:47.530 --> 02:02:51.930
'Tis he the common peoplelove so much.

2041
02:02:51.930 --> 02:02:53.530
Myself hath often heardthem say

2042
02:02:53.530 --> 02:02:55.130
when I have walked like aprivate man

2043
02:02:55.130 --> 02:02:56.800
that Lucius' banishmentwas wrongfully,

2044
02:02:56.800 --> 02:02:59.030
and they have wished thatLucius were their emperor.

2045
02:02:59.030 --> 02:03:00.200
Why should you fear?

2046
02:03:00.200 --> 02:03:01.670
Is not your city strong?

2047
02:03:01.670 --> 02:03:03.370
Ay, but the citizens favorLucius

2048
02:03:03.370 --> 02:03:06.130
and will revolt from me tosuccor him.

2049
02:03:06.130 --> 02:03:10.370
King, be thy thoughtsimperious like thy name.

2050
02:03:10.370 --> 02:03:14.230
Is the sun dimmed, thatgnats do fly in it?

2051
02:03:14.230 --> 02:03:16.670
The eagle suffers littlebirds to sing

2052
02:03:16.670 --> 02:03:18.800
and is not careful whatthey mean thereby,

2053
02:03:18.800 --> 02:03:20.630
knowing that with theshadow of his wings

2054
02:03:20.630 --> 02:03:23.100
he can at pleasure stinttheir melody.

2055
02:03:23.100 --> 02:03:28.970
Even so mayest thou thegiddy men of Rome.

2056
02:03:28.970 --> 02:03:32.900
Then cheer thy spirit; forknow thou, Emperor,

2057
02:03:32.900 --> 02:03:35.530
I will enchant the oldAndronicus

2058
02:03:35.530 --> 02:03:38.170
with words more sweet andyet more dangerous

2059
02:03:38.170 --> 02:03:40.570
than baits to fish orhoney-stalks to sheep,

2060
02:03:40.570 --> 02:03:42.470
when as the one is woundedwith the bait,

2061
02:03:42.470 --> 02:03:44.330
the other rotted withdelicious feed.

2062
02:03:44.330 --> 02:03:47.870
But he will not entreathis son for us.

2063
02:03:47.870 --> 02:03:49.830
If Tamora entreat him,then he will;

2064
02:03:49.830 --> 02:03:53.200
for I can smooth and fillhis aged ears

2065
02:03:53.200 --> 02:03:56.500
with golden promises,that, were his heart

2066
02:03:56.500 --> 02:03:58.830
almost impregnable, hisold ears deaf,

2067
02:03:58.830 --> 02:04:02.470
yet should both ear andheart obey my tongue.

2068
02:04:02.470 --> 02:04:04.200
Go thou before.

2069
02:04:04.200 --> 02:04:05.830
Be our ambassador.

2070
02:04:05.830 --> 02:04:07.970
Say that the emperorrequests a parley

2071
02:04:07.970 --> 02:04:10.170
of warlike Lucius, andappoint the meeting

2072
02:04:10.170 --> 02:04:15.730
even at his father'shouse, the old Andronicus.

2073
02:04:15.730 --> 02:04:18.800
Aemilius, do this messagehonorably.

2074
02:04:18.800 --> 02:04:21.300
And if he stand on hostagefor his safety,

2075
02:04:21.300 --> 02:04:23.770
bid him demand what pledgewill please him best.

2076
02:04:23.770 --> 02:04:27.370
Your bidding shall I doeffectually.

2077
02:04:27.370 --> 02:04:29.670
Now will I to that oldAndronicus,

2078
02:04:29.670 --> 02:04:32.370
and temper him with allthe art I have

2079
02:04:32.370 --> 02:04:35.830
to pluck proud Lucius fromthe warlike Goths.

2080
02:04:35.830 --> 02:04:40.300
And now, sweet emperor, beblithe again

2081
02:04:40.300 --> 02:04:43.700
and bury all thy fears inmy devices.

2082
02:04:43.700 --> 02:04:47.000
Then go incessantly, andplead to him.

2083
02:05:24.500 --> 02:05:27.670
Approved warriors and myfaithful friends,

2084
02:05:27.670 --> 02:05:30.100
I have received lettersfrom great Rome,

2085
02:05:30.100 --> 02:05:32.930
which signifies what hatethey bear their emperor

2086
02:05:32.930 --> 02:05:35.170
and how desirous of oursight they are.

2087
02:05:35.170 --> 02:05:38.270
Therefore, great lords, be,as your titles witness,

2088
02:05:38.270 --> 02:05:41.500
imperious and impatient ofyour wrongs;

2089
02:05:41.500 --> 02:05:44.270
and wherein Rome hath doneyou any scathe,

2090
02:05:44.270 --> 02:05:48.730
let him make treblesatisfaction.

2091
02:05:48.730 --> 02:05:53.930
Brave slip, sprung fromthe great Andronicus,

2092
02:05:53.930 --> 02:05:58.400
whose name was once ourterror, now our comfort,

2093
02:05:58.400 --> 02:06:01.800
whose high exploits andhonorable deeds

2094
02:06:01.800 --> 02:06:05.870
ingrateful Rome requiteswith foul contempt,

2095
02:06:05.870 --> 02:06:10.270
be bold in us: we'llfollow where thou lead'st,

2096
02:06:10.270 --> 02:06:13.330
like stinging bees inhottest summer's day,

2097
02:06:13.330 --> 02:06:17.370
led by their master to theflowered fields,

2098
02:06:17.370 --> 02:06:21.070
and be avenged on cursedTamora.

2099
02:06:21.070 --> 02:06:25.100
And as he saith, so say weall with him.

2100
02:06:25.100 --> 02:06:26.430
Ay.

2101
02:06:26.430 --> 02:06:29.430
I humbly thank him, and Ithank you all.

2102
02:06:29.430 --> 02:06:34.530
But who comes here, led bya lusty Goth?

2103
02:06:34.530 --> 02:06:37.730
Renowned Lucius, from ourtroops I strayed

2104
02:06:37.730 --> 02:06:39.800
to gaze upon a ruinousmonastery.

2105
02:06:39.800 --> 02:06:41.770
And as I earnestly did fixmine eye

2106
02:06:41.770 --> 02:06:43.000
upon the wasted building,

2107
02:06:43.000 --> 02:06:45.470
suddenly I heard a childcry underneath a wall.

2108
02:06:45.470 --> 02:06:47.530
I made unto the noise,when soon I heard

2109
02:06:47.530 --> 02:06:50.630
the crying babe controlledwith this discourse:

2110
02:06:50.630 --> 02:06:54.400
"Peace, tawny slave, halfme and half thy dame!

2111
02:06:54.400 --> 02:06:57.070
"Did not thy hue bewraywhose brat thou art,

2112
02:06:57.070 --> 02:06:59.530
"had nature lent thee butthy mother's look,

2113
02:06:59.530 --> 02:07:01.600
"villain, thou mightsthave been an emperor.

2114
02:07:01.600 --> 02:07:03.900
"But where the bull andcow are both milk-white,

2115
02:07:03.900 --> 02:07:06.330
"they never do beget acoal-black calf.

2116
02:07:06.330 --> 02:07:07.770
Peace, villain, peace! "

2117
02:07:07.770 --> 02:07:09.030
even thus he rates thebabe

2118
02:07:09.030 --> 02:07:11.370
"For I must bear thee to atrusty Goth,

2119
02:07:11.370 --> 02:07:13.630
"who, when he knows thouart the empress' babe,

2120
02:07:13.630 --> 02:07:15.800
will hold thee dearly forthy mother's sake."

2121
02:07:15.800 --> 02:07:18.270
With this, my weapondrawn, I rushed upon him,

2122
02:07:18.270 --> 02:07:20.470
surprised him suddenly,and brought him hither

2123
02:07:20.470 --> 02:07:21.970
to use as you thinkneedful of the man.

2124
02:07:21.970 --> 02:07:26.200
O, worthy Goth, this isthe incarnate devil

2125
02:07:26.200 --> 02:07:29.230
that robbed Andronicus ofhis good hand.

2126
02:07:29.230 --> 02:07:33.630
This is the pearl thatpleased your empress' eye.

2127
02:07:33.630 --> 02:07:38.330
And here's the base fruitof her burning lust.

2128
02:07:38.330 --> 02:07:41.570
Say, wall-eyed slave,whither wouldst thou convey

2129
02:07:41.570 --> 02:07:44.330
this growing image of thyfiend-like face?

2130
02:07:44.330 --> 02:07:46.300
Why dost not speak?

2131
02:07:46.300 --> 02:07:48.530
What, deaf?

2132
02:07:48.530 --> 02:07:50.370
Not a word?

2133
02:07:50.370 --> 02:07:51.670
A halter, soldiers!

2134
02:07:51.670 --> 02:07:52.930
Hang him on this tree,

2135
02:07:52.930 --> 02:07:55.330
and by his side his fruitof bastardy.

2136
02:07:55.330 --> 02:07:57.630
Touch not the boy; he isof royal blood.

2137
02:07:57.630 --> 02:07:59.770
Too like the sire for everbeing good.

2138
02:07:59.770 --> 02:08:03.270
First hang the child, thathe may see it sprawl,

2139
02:08:03.270 --> 02:08:05.970
a sight to vex thefather's soul withal.

2140
02:08:05.970 --> 02:08:07.370
Get me a ladder.

2141
02:08:07.370 --> 02:08:08.930
Lucius, save the child,

2142
02:08:08.930 --> 02:08:10.930
and bear it from me to theempress.

2143
02:08:10.930 --> 02:08:13.830
If thou do this, I'll showthee wondrous things

2144
02:08:13.830 --> 02:08:16.000
that highly may advantagethee to hear.

2145
02:08:16.000 --> 02:08:19.330
If thou wilt not, befallwhat may befall,

2146
02:08:19.330 --> 02:08:22.100
I'll speak no more butvengeance rot you all!

2147
02:08:22.100 --> 02:08:24.700
Say on; and if it pleaseme which thou speak'st,

2148
02:08:24.700 --> 02:08:26.670
thy child shall live, andI will see it nourished.

2149
02:08:26.670 --> 02:08:28.370
And if it please thee.

2150
02:08:28.370 --> 02:08:29.730
Why, assure thee, Lucius,

2151
02:08:29.730 --> 02:08:32.970
'twill vex thy soul tohear what I shall speak;

2152
02:08:32.970 --> 02:08:36.200
for I must talk of murders,rapes, and massacres,

2153
02:08:36.200 --> 02:08:38.830
acts of black night,abominable deeds,

2154
02:08:38.830 --> 02:08:41.630
complots of mischief,treason, villainies,

2155
02:08:41.630 --> 02:08:44.830
ruthful to hear, yetpiteously performed.

2156
02:08:44.830 --> 02:08:47.200
And this shall all beburied in my death,

2157
02:08:47.200 --> 02:08:50.100
unless thou swear to me mychild shall live.

2158
02:08:50.100 --> 02:08:51.200
Tell on thy mind.

2159
02:08:51.200 --> 02:08:52.800
I say thy child shalllive.

2160
02:08:52.800 --> 02:08:54.500
Swear that he shall, andthen I will begin.

2161
02:08:54.500 --> 02:08:55.630
Who should I swear by?

2162
02:08:55.630 --> 02:08:56.870
Thou believest no god.

2163
02:08:56.870 --> 02:08:58.900
That granted, how canstthou believe an oath?

2164
02:08:58.900 --> 02:09:01.700
What if I do not, asindeed I do not?

2165
02:09:01.700 --> 02:09:04.130
Yet, for I know thou artreligious

2166
02:09:04.130 --> 02:09:07.270
and hast a thing withinthee called conscience;

2167
02:09:07.270 --> 02:09:09.200
therefore, I urge thyoath.

2168
02:09:09.200 --> 02:09:13.300
For that I know an idiotholds his bauble for a god,

2169
02:09:13.300 --> 02:09:16.430
and keeps the oath whichby that god he swears,

2170
02:09:16.430 --> 02:09:17.870
to that I'll urge him.

2171
02:09:17.870 --> 02:09:20.600
Therefore, thou shalt vowby that same god

2172
02:09:20.600 --> 02:09:22.570
what god soe'er it be thatthou adorest

2173
02:09:22.570 --> 02:09:23.730
and hast in reverence

2174
02:09:23.730 --> 02:09:26.170
to save my boy, to nourishand bring him up;

2175
02:09:26.170 --> 02:09:31.100
or else I will discovernought to thee.

2176
02:09:31.100 --> 02:09:36.200
Even by my god, I swear tothee I will.

2177
02:09:58.030 --> 02:10:01.970
First know thou, I begothim on the empress.

2178
02:10:01.970 --> 02:10:04.300
O, most insatiate andluxurious woman!

2179
02:10:04.300 --> 02:10:08.200
Tut, Lucius; this was buta deed of charity

2180
02:10:08.200 --> 02:10:10.900
to that which thou shalthear of me anon.

2181
02:10:10.900 --> 02:10:15.630
'Twas her two sons thatmurdered Bassianus.

2182
02:10:15.630 --> 02:10:18.400
They cut thy sister'stongue and ravished her

2183
02:10:18.400 --> 02:10:22.300
and cut her hands andtrimmed her as thousaw'st.

2184
02:10:22.300 --> 02:10:23.830
O, detestable villain!

2185
02:10:23.830 --> 02:10:25.030
Call'st thou thattrimming?

2186
02:10:25.030 --> 02:10:27.870
Why, she was washed andcut and trimmed,

2187
02:10:27.870 --> 02:10:30.830
and 'twas trim sport for themwhich had the doing of it.

2188
02:10:30.830 --> 02:10:32.970
O, barbarous beastlyvillains like thyself!

2189
02:10:32.970 --> 02:10:35.700
Indeed, I was their tutorto instruct them.

2190
02:10:35.700 --> 02:10:38.500
That codding spirit hadthey from their mother,

2191
02:10:38.500 --> 02:10:41.600
as sure a card as ever wonthe set.

2192
02:10:41.600 --> 02:10:44.970
That bloody mind, I think,they learned of me,

2193
02:10:44.970 --> 02:10:47.670
as true a dog as everfought at head.

2194
02:10:47.670 --> 02:10:50.530
Well, let my deeds bewitness of my worth.

2195
02:10:50.530 --> 02:10:54.230
I trained thy brethren tothat guileful hole

2196
02:10:54.230 --> 02:10:57.200
where the dead corpse ofBassianus lay.

2197
02:10:57.200 --> 02:10:59.970
I wrote the letter thatthy father found

2198
02:10:59.970 --> 02:11:02.570
and hid the gold withinthat letter mentioned,

2199
02:11:02.570 --> 02:11:05.570
confederate with the queenand her two sons.

2200
02:11:05.570 --> 02:11:08.570
And what not done, thatthou hast cause to rue,

2201
02:11:08.570 --> 02:11:11.470
wherein I had no stroke ofmischief in it?

2202
02:11:11.470 --> 02:11:14.570
I played the cheater forthy father's hand,

2203
02:11:14.570 --> 02:11:17.000
and when I had it, drewmyself apart

2204
02:11:17.000 --> 02:11:20.070
and almost broke my heartwith extreme laughter.

2205
02:11:20.070 --> 02:11:22.300
I pried me through thecrevice of a wall,

2206
02:11:22.300 --> 02:11:25.330
when, for his hand, he hadhis two sons' heads,

2207
02:11:25.330 --> 02:11:28.870
beheld his tears, andlaughed so heartily

2208
02:11:28.870 --> 02:11:32.400
that both mine eyes wererainy like to his.

2209
02:11:32.400 --> 02:11:34.600
And when I told theempress of this sport,

2210
02:11:34.600 --> 02:11:37.300
she sounded almost at mypleasing tale

2211
02:11:37.300 --> 02:11:40.200
and for my tidings gave metwenty kisses.

2212
02:11:40.200 --> 02:11:44.500
What, canst thou say allthis and never blush?

2213
02:11:44.500 --> 02:11:47.970
Ay, like a black dog, asthe saying is.

2214
02:11:47.970 --> 02:11:51.130
Art thou not sorry forthese heinous deeds?

2215
02:11:51.130 --> 02:11:55.270
Ay, that I had not done athousand more.

2216
02:11:55.270 --> 02:11:58.330
Even now I curse the day and yet, I think,

2217
02:11:58.330 --> 02:12:00.730
few come within thecompass of my curse

2218
02:12:00.730 --> 02:12:03.670
wherein I did not somenotorious ill

2219
02:12:03.670 --> 02:12:07.100
as kill a man, or elsedevise his death,

2220
02:12:07.100 --> 02:12:10.400
ravish a maid, or plot theway to do it,

2221
02:12:10.400 --> 02:12:13.730
accuse some innocent andforswear myself,

2222
02:12:13.730 --> 02:12:16.700
set deadly enmity betweentwo friends,

2223
02:12:16.700 --> 02:12:19.970
make poor men's cattlebreak their necks,

2224
02:12:19.970 --> 02:12:23.530
set fire on barns andhaystacks in the night,

2225
02:12:23.530 --> 02:12:27.030
and bid the owners quenchthem with their tears.

2226
02:12:27.030 --> 02:12:29.900
Oft have I digged up deadmen from their graves

2227
02:12:29.900 --> 02:12:32.500
and set them upright attheir dear friends' door

2228
02:12:32.500 --> 02:12:35.570
even when their sorrowsalmost was forgot

2229
02:12:35.570 --> 02:12:38.100
and on their skins, as onthe bark of trees,

2230
02:12:38.100 --> 02:12:40.830
have with my knife carvedin Roman letters,

2231
02:12:40.830 --> 02:12:43.770
"Let not your sorrow die,though I am dead."

2232
02:12:43.770 --> 02:12:47.630
Tut, I have done athousand dreadful things

2233
02:12:47.630 --> 02:12:50.300
as willingly as one wouldkill a fly,

2234
02:12:50.300 --> 02:12:53.500
and nothing grieves meheartily indeed

2235
02:12:53.500 --> 02:12:56.000
but that I cannot do tenthousand more.

2236
02:12:56.000 --> 02:12:57.770
Bring down the devil, forhe must not die

2237
02:12:57.770 --> 02:12:59.670
so sweet a death ashanging presently.

2238
02:12:59.670 --> 02:13:02.130
If there be devils, wouldI were a devil,

2239
02:13:02.130 --> 02:13:04.270
to live and burn ineverlasting fire,

2240
02:13:04.270 --> 02:13:06.800
so I might have yourcompany in hell

2241
02:13:06.800 --> 02:13:09.530
but to torment you with mybitter tongue!

2242
02:13:09.530 --> 02:13:13.330
Sirs, stop his mouth, andlet him speak no more!

2243
02:13:13.330 --> 02:13:15.870
My lord, there is amessenger from Rome

2244
02:13:15.870 --> 02:13:17.470
desires to be admitted toyour presence.

2245
02:13:17.470 --> 02:13:21.570
Let him come near.

2246
02:13:21.570 --> 02:13:23.330
Welcome, Aemilius.

2247
02:13:23.330 --> 02:13:24.730
What's the news from Rome?

2248
02:13:24.730 --> 02:13:27.700
Lord Lucius, and youprinces of the Goths,

2249
02:13:27.700 --> 02:13:30.230
the Roman emperor greetsyou all by me,

2250
02:13:30.230 --> 02:13:32.530
and, for he understandsyou are in arms,

2251
02:13:32.530 --> 02:13:35.330
he craves a parley at yourfather's house,

2252
02:13:35.330 --> 02:13:37.170
willing you to demand yourhostages,

2253
02:13:37.170 --> 02:13:39.500
and they shall beimmediately delivered.

2254
02:13:39.500 --> 02:13:42.200
What says our general?

2255
02:13:42.200 --> 02:13:44.700
Aemilius, let the emperorgive his pledges

2256
02:13:44.700 --> 02:13:47.500
unto my father and my uncleMarcus, and we will come.

2257
02:13:47.500 --> 02:13:49.500
March away!

2258
02:14:12.070 --> 02:14:14.900
Thus, in this strange andsad habiliment,

2259
02:14:14.900 --> 02:14:17.230
I will encounter withAndronicus

2260
02:14:17.230 --> 02:14:20.370
and say I am Revenge, sentfrom below

2261
02:14:20.370 --> 02:14:25.030
to join with him and righthis heinous wrongs.

2262
02:14:25.030 --> 02:14:26.900
Knock at his study, wherethey say he keeps

2263
02:14:26.900 --> 02:14:29.930
to ruminate strange plotsof dire revenge.

2264
02:14:29.930 --> 02:14:32.430
Tell him Revenge is cometo join with him,

2265
02:14:32.430 --> 02:14:34.730
and work confusion on hisenemies.

2266
02:14:47.500 --> 02:14:51.430
Who doth molest mycontemplation?

2267
02:14:51.430 --> 02:14:54.070
Is it your trick to makeme ope the door,

2268
02:14:54.070 --> 02:14:56.700
that so my sad decrees mayfly away

2269
02:14:56.700 --> 02:14:59.070
and all my study be to noeffect?

2270
02:14:59.070 --> 02:15:01.770
You are deceived; for whatI mean to do

2271
02:15:01.770 --> 02:15:05.070
see here in bloody lines Ihave set down,

2272
02:15:05.070 --> 02:15:07.670
and what is written shallbe executed.

2273
02:15:07.670 --> 02:15:11.200
Titus, I am come to talkwith thee.

2274
02:15:11.200 --> 02:15:14.870
No, not a word.

2275
02:15:14.870 --> 02:15:16.570
How can I grace my talk,

2276
02:15:16.570 --> 02:15:19.470
wanting a hand to give itthat accord?

2277
02:15:19.470 --> 02:15:22.230
You have the odds of me;therefore no more.

2278
02:15:22.230 --> 02:15:25.500
If thou didst know me,thou wouldst talk with me.

2279
02:15:25.500 --> 02:15:28.570
I am not mad; I know theewell enough.

2280
02:15:28.570 --> 02:15:30.270
Witness this wretchedstump.

2281
02:15:30.270 --> 02:15:32.400
Witness these crimsonlines.

2282
02:15:32.400 --> 02:15:35.230
Witness these trenchesmade by grief and care.

2283
02:15:35.230 --> 02:15:37.800
Witness the tiring day andheavy night.

2284
02:15:37.800 --> 02:15:40.030
Witness all sorrow that Iknow thee well

2285
02:15:40.030 --> 02:15:41.900
for our proud empress,mighty Tamora.

2286
02:15:41.900 --> 02:15:44.630
Is not thy coming for myother hand?

2287
02:15:44.630 --> 02:15:48.600
Know thou, sad man, I amnot Tamora.

2288
02:15:48.600 --> 02:15:52.600
She is thy enemy and I thyfriend.

2289
02:15:52.600 --> 02:15:56.470
I am Revenge, sent fromthe infernal kingdom

2290
02:15:56.470 --> 02:15:58.830
to ease the gnawingvulture of thy mind

2291
02:15:58.830 --> 02:16:04.030
by working wreakfulvengeance on thy foes.

2292
02:16:04.030 --> 02:16:08.970
Therefore, come down andwelcome me to this world'slight.

2293
02:16:08.970 --> 02:16:13.470
Confer with me of murderand of death;

2294
02:16:13.470 --> 02:16:15.770
There's not a hollow caveor lurking place,

2295
02:16:15.770 --> 02:16:18.400
no vast obscurity or mistyvale

2296
02:16:18.400 --> 02:16:20.370
where bloody murder ordetested rape

2297
02:16:20.370 --> 02:16:23.630
can couch for fear but Iwill find them out

2298
02:16:23.630 --> 02:16:27.170
and in their ear tell themmy dreadful name,

2299
02:16:27.170 --> 02:16:31.100
Revenge, which makes thefoul offender quake.

2300
02:16:31.100 --> 02:16:33.830
Art thou Revenge?

2301
02:16:33.830 --> 02:16:37.930
And art thou sent to me to bea torment to mine enemies?

2302
02:16:37.930 --> 02:16:44.400
I am; therefore come downand welcome me.

2303
02:16:44.400 --> 02:16:47.170
Do me some service ere Icome to thee.

2304
02:16:47.170 --> 02:16:50.400
Lo, by thy side where Rapeand Murder stands.

2305
02:16:50.400 --> 02:16:52.870
Now give some surance thatthou art Revenge.

2306
02:16:52.870 --> 02:16:55.470
Stab them, or tear them onthy chariot wheel.

2307
02:16:55.470 --> 02:16:57.430
And then I'll come and bethy wagoner

2308
02:16:57.430 --> 02:16:59.430
and whirl along with theeabout the globes.

2309
02:16:59.430 --> 02:17:02.270
Provide thee two properpalfreys, black as jet,

2310
02:17:02.270 --> 02:17:04.800
to hale thy vengeful wagonswift away,

2311
02:17:04.800 --> 02:17:07.730
and find out murderers intheir guilty caves.

2312
02:17:07.730 --> 02:17:10.670
And when thy car is loadenwith their heads,

2313
02:17:10.670 --> 02:17:13.900
I will dismount, and bythy wagon wheel

2314
02:17:13.900 --> 02:17:17.530
trot like a servilefootman, all day long,

2315
02:17:17.530 --> 02:17:20.000
even from Hyperion'srising in the east

2316
02:17:20.000 --> 02:17:22.370
until his very downfall inthe sea.

2317
02:17:22.370 --> 02:17:27.130
And day by day I'll dothis heavy task,

2318
02:17:27.130 --> 02:17:30.400
so thou destroy Rapine andMurder there.

2319
02:17:30.400 --> 02:17:34.930
These are my ministers andcome with me.

2320
02:17:34.930 --> 02:17:37.730
Are they thy ministers?

2321
02:17:37.730 --> 02:17:40.200
What are they called?

2322
02:17:40.200 --> 02:17:43.470
Rape and Murder; thereforecalled so

2323
02:17:43.470 --> 02:17:47.100
'cause they take vengeanceof such kind of men.

2324
02:17:47.100 --> 02:17:53.370
Good Lord, how like theempress' sons they are!

2325
02:17:53.370 --> 02:17:58.230
And you the empress!

2326
02:17:58.230 --> 02:18:06.600
But we worldly men havemiserable, mad, mistaking eyes.

2327
02:18:06.600 --> 02:18:11.770
O, sweet Revenge, now do Icome to thee.

2328
02:18:11.770 --> 02:18:14.570
And, if one arm's embracementwill content thee,

2329
02:18:14.570 --> 02:18:21.370
I will embrace thee in itby and by.

2330
02:18:21.370 --> 02:18:23.870
This closing with him fitshis lunacy.

2331
02:18:23.870 --> 02:18:26.430
Whate'er I forge to feedhis brain-sick humors

2332
02:18:26.430 --> 02:18:28.730
do you uphold and maintainin your speeches,

2333
02:18:28.730 --> 02:18:31.200
for now he firmly takes mefor Revenge.

2334
02:18:31.200 --> 02:18:33.430
And, being credulous inthis mad thought,

2335
02:18:33.430 --> 02:18:35.730
I'll make him send forLucius his son,

2336
02:18:35.730 --> 02:18:38.000
and whilst I at a banquethold him sure,

2337
02:18:38.000 --> 02:18:40.130
I'll find some cunningpractice out of hand

2338
02:18:40.130 --> 02:18:42.370
to scatter and dispersethe giddy Goths,

2339
02:18:42.370 --> 02:18:44.170
or at the least, make themhis enemies.

2340
02:18:44.170 --> 02:18:52.470
See, here he comes, and Imust ply my theme.

2341
02:18:52.470 --> 02:18:56.170
Long have I been forlorn,and all for thee.

2342
02:18:56.170 --> 02:19:01.370
Welcome, dread Fury, to mywoeful house.

2343
02:19:01.370 --> 02:19:06.070
Rapine and Murder, you arewelcome too.

2344
02:19:06.070 --> 02:19:11.230
How like the empress andher sons you are.

2345
02:19:11.230 --> 02:19:13.370
Well are you fitted, hadyou but a Moor.

2346
02:19:13.370 --> 02:19:15.900
Could not all hell affordyou such a devil?

2347
02:19:15.900 --> 02:19:18.030
For well I wot the empressnever wags

2348
02:19:18.030 --> 02:19:22.370
but in her company thereis a Moor.

2349
02:19:22.370 --> 02:19:24.230
And, would you representour queen aright,

2350
02:19:24.230 --> 02:19:28.070
it were convenient you hadsuch a devil.

2351
02:19:28.070 --> 02:19:31.770
But welcome as you are.

2352
02:19:31.770 --> 02:19:33.870
What shall we do?

2353
02:19:33.870 --> 02:19:36.170
What wouldst thou have usdo, Andronicus?

2354
02:19:36.170 --> 02:19:39.900
Show me a murderer; I'lldeal with him.

2355
02:19:39.900 --> 02:19:41.900
Show me a villain thathath done a rape,

2356
02:19:41.900 --> 02:19:43.770
and I am sent to berevenged on him.

2357
02:19:43.770 --> 02:19:45.930
Show me a thousand thathath done thee wrong,

2358
02:19:45.930 --> 02:19:48.930
and I will be revenged onthem all.

2359
02:19:48.930 --> 02:19:53.830
Look round about thewicked streets of Rome,

2360
02:19:53.830 --> 02:19:56.530
and when thou find'st aman that's like thyself,

2361
02:19:56.530 --> 02:20:00.330
good Murder, stab him;he's a murderer.

2362
02:20:00.330 --> 02:20:02.770
Go thou with him, and whenit is thy hap

2363
02:20:02.770 --> 02:20:04.930
to find another that islike to thee,

2364
02:20:04.930 --> 02:20:09.330
good Rapine, stab him;he's a ravisher.

2365
02:20:09.330 --> 02:20:13.300
Go thou with them, and inthe emperor's court

2366
02:20:13.300 --> 02:20:15.570
there is a queen, attendedby a Moor.

2367
02:20:15.570 --> 02:20:17.730
Well shalt thou know herby thine own proportion,

2368
02:20:17.730 --> 02:20:21.530
for up and down she dothresemble thee.

2369
02:20:21.530 --> 02:20:25.900
I pray thee, do on themsome violent death.

2370
02:20:25.900 --> 02:20:30.070
They have been violent tome and mine.

2371
02:20:30.070 --> 02:20:32.830
Well hast thou lessonedus.

2372
02:20:32.830 --> 02:20:35.430
This shall we do.

2373
02:20:35.430 --> 02:20:37.870
But would it please thee,good Andronicus,

2374
02:20:37.870 --> 02:20:40.600
to send for Lucius, thythrice-valiant son,

2375
02:20:40.600 --> 02:20:43.530
who leads towards Rome aband of warlike Goths,

2376
02:20:43.530 --> 02:20:46.130
and bid him come andbanquet at thy house.

2377
02:20:46.130 --> 02:20:49.500
When he is here, even atthy solemn feast,

2378
02:20:49.500 --> 02:20:52.870
I will bring in theempress and her sons,

2379
02:20:52.870 --> 02:20:55.570
the emperor himself, andall thy foes.

2380
02:20:55.570 --> 02:20:58.430
And at thy mercy shallthey stoop and kneel,

2381
02:20:58.430 --> 02:21:01.600
and on them shalt thouease thy angry heart.

2382
02:21:01.600 --> 02:21:05.670
What says Andronicus tothis device?

2383
02:21:05.670 --> 02:21:09.600
Marcus, my brother!

2384
02:21:09.600 --> 02:21:15.870
'Tis sad Titus calls.

2385
02:21:15.870 --> 02:21:19.570
Go, gentle Marcus, to thynephew Lucius.

2386
02:21:19.570 --> 02:21:23.070
Thou shalt inquire him outamong the Goths.

2387
02:21:23.070 --> 02:21:25.270
Bid him repair to me, andbring with him

2388
02:21:25.270 --> 02:21:28.370
some of the chiefestprinces of the Goths.

2389
02:21:28.370 --> 02:21:30.970
Bid him encamp hissoldiers where they are.

2390
02:21:30.970 --> 02:21:36.270
Tell him the emperor andthe empress too

2391
02:21:36.270 --> 02:21:39.870
feast at my house, and heshall feast with them.

2392
02:21:39.870 --> 02:21:43.070
This do thou for my love,and so let him,

2393
02:21:43.070 --> 02:21:45.630
as he regards his agedfather's life.

2394
02:21:45.630 --> 02:21:48.900
This shall I do, and soonreturn again.

2395
02:21:53.370 --> 02:21:56.630
Now will I hence about thybusiness,

2396
02:21:56.630 --> 02:21:58.770
and take my ministersalong with me.

2397
02:21:58.770 --> 02:22:00.500
Nay, nay,

2398
02:22:00.500 --> 02:22:05.070
let Rape and Murder staywith me,

2399
02:22:05.070 --> 02:22:08.430
or else I'll call mybrother back again

2400
02:22:08.430 --> 02:22:13.330
and cleave to no revengebut Lucius.

2401
02:22:13.330 --> 02:22:14.570
What say you, boys?

2402
02:22:14.570 --> 02:22:16.000
Will you abide with him

2403
02:22:16.000 --> 02:22:17.670
whiles I go tell my lordthe emperor

2404
02:22:17.670 --> 02:22:19.670
how I have governed ourdetermined jest?

2405
02:22:19.670 --> 02:22:22.700
Yield to his humor, smoothand speak him fair,

2406
02:22:22.700 --> 02:22:26.470
and tarry with him till Iturn again.

2407
02:22:26.470 --> 02:22:31.970
I knew them all, thoughthey suppose me mad,

2408
02:22:31.970 --> 02:22:35.970
and will o'er reach themin their own devices

2409
02:22:35.970 --> 02:22:39.570
a pair of hell-hounds andtheir cursed dam.

2410
02:22:39.570 --> 02:22:41.900
Madam, depart at pleasure.

2411
02:22:41.900 --> 02:22:45.100
Leave us here.

2412
02:22:45.100 --> 02:22:47.000
Farewell, Andronicus.

2413
02:22:47.000 --> 02:22:51.170
Revenge now goes to lay acomplot

2414
02:22:51.170 --> 02:22:53.270
to betray thy foes.

2415
02:22:53.270 --> 02:22:54.630
I know thou dost;

2416
02:22:54.630 --> 02:22:57.130
and sweet Revenge,farewell.

2417
02:23:06.530 --> 02:23:12.730
Tell us, old man, howshall we be employed?

2418
02:23:12.730 --> 02:23:16.830
Tut, I have work enoughfor you to do.

2419
02:23:16.830 --> 02:23:22.770
Publius, come hither,Caius, and Valentine.

2420
02:23:22.770 --> 02:23:24.330
What is your will?

2421
02:23:24.330 --> 02:23:26.030
Know you these two?

2422
02:23:26.030 --> 02:23:28.800
The empress' sons, I takethem: Chiron, Demetrius.

2423
02:23:28.800 --> 02:23:35.200
Fie, Publius, fie; thouart too much deceived.

2424
02:23:35.200 --> 02:23:40.670
The one is Murder, andRape is the other's name.

2425
02:23:40.670 --> 02:23:45.830
And therefore bind them,gentle Publius

2426
02:23:45.830 --> 02:23:50.400
Caius and Valentine, layhands on them.

2427
02:23:50.400 --> 02:23:52.770
Oft have you heard me wishfor such an hour,

2428
02:23:52.770 --> 02:23:56.430
and now I find it;therefore bind them sure,

2429
02:23:56.430 --> 02:24:00.970
and stop their mouths ifthey begin to cry.

2430
02:24:00.970 --> 02:24:02.670
Villains, forbear!

2431
02:24:02.670 --> 02:24:04.400
We are the empress' sons.

2432
02:24:04.400 --> 02:24:09.400
And therefore do what weare commanded.

2433
02:24:09.400 --> 02:24:11.170
Stop close their mouths.

2434
02:24:11.170 --> 02:24:13.770
Let them not speak a word.

2435
02:24:13.770 --> 02:24:16.030
Is he sure bound?

2436
02:24:16.030 --> 02:24:18.030
Look that you bind themfast.

2437
02:24:51.630 --> 02:24:53.070
Come, come, Lavinia.

2438
02:24:53.070 --> 02:24:54.800
Look, thy foes are bound.

2439
02:24:54.800 --> 02:24:57.470
Sirs, stop their mouths.

2440
02:24:57.470 --> 02:25:01.230
Let them not speak to me.

2441
02:25:01.230 --> 02:25:07.730
But let them hear whatfearful words I utter.

2442
02:25:07.730 --> 02:25:11.630
O, villains, Chiron andDemetrius.

2443
02:25:11.630 --> 02:25:15.200
Here stands the spring whomyou have stained with mud;

2444
02:25:15.200 --> 02:25:18.530
this goodly summer withyour winter mixed.

2445
02:25:18.530 --> 02:25:22.330
You killed her husband,and for that vile fault

2446
02:25:22.330 --> 02:25:25.230
two of her brothers werecondemned to death,

2447
02:25:25.230 --> 02:25:28.030
my hand cut off and made amerry jest.

2448
02:25:28.030 --> 02:25:30.070
Both her sweet hands, hertongue,

2449
02:25:30.070 --> 02:25:32.230
and that more dear thanhands or tongue

2450
02:25:32.230 --> 02:25:35.430
her spotless chastity

2451
02:25:35.430 --> 02:25:41.030
inhuman traitors, youconstrained and forced.

2452
02:25:41.030 --> 02:25:43.500
What would you say, if Ishould let you speak?

2453
02:25:43.500 --> 02:25:48.330
Villains, for shame youcould not beg for grace.

2454
02:25:48.330 --> 02:25:52.730
Hark, wretches, how I meanto martyr you.

2455
02:25:52.730 --> 02:25:55.670
This one hand yet is leftto cut your throats,

2456
02:25:55.670 --> 02:25:58.770
whiles that Lavinia 'tweenher stumps doth hold

2457
02:25:58.770 --> 02:26:01.470
the basin that receivesyour guilty blood.

2458
02:26:01.470 --> 02:26:03.870
You know your mother meansto feast with me

2459
02:26:03.870 --> 02:26:07.900
and calls herself Revenge,and thinks me mad.

2460
02:26:07.900 --> 02:26:11.930
Hark, wretches; I willgrind your bones to dust,

2461
02:26:11.930 --> 02:26:14.670
and with your blood and itI'll make a paste;

2462
02:26:14.670 --> 02:26:18.130
and of the paste a coffinI will rear

2463
02:26:18.130 --> 02:26:20.730
and make two pasties ofyour shameful heads

2464
02:26:20.730 --> 02:26:24.930
and bid that strumpet,your unhallowed dam,

2465
02:26:24.930 --> 02:26:29.030
like to the earth, swallowher own increase.

2466
02:26:29.030 --> 02:26:32.170
This is the feast that Ihave bid her to

2467
02:26:32.170 --> 02:26:34.600
and this the banquet sheshall surfeit on;

2468
02:26:34.600 --> 02:26:37.470
for worse than Philomelyou used my daughter,

2469
02:26:37.470 --> 02:26:41.030
and worse than Progne Iwill be revenged.

2470
02:26:41.030 --> 02:26:43.230
And now prepare yourthroats.

2471
02:26:52.330 --> 02:26:59.230
Lavinia, come, receive theblood.

2472
02:26:59.230 --> 02:27:02.930
Come, come, be every oneofficious

2473
02:27:02.930 --> 02:27:06.330
to make this banquet,which I wish may prove

2474
02:27:06.330 --> 02:27:11.070
more stern and bloody thanthe centaurs' feast.

2475
02:27:37.870 --> 02:27:41.230
Bring them in, for I willplay the cook

2476
02:27:41.230 --> 02:27:44.670
and see them ready againsttheir mother comes.

2477
02:28:38.500 --> 02:28:41.970
Uncle Marcus, since 'tismy father's mind

2478
02:28:41.970 --> 02:28:44.470
that I repair to Rome, Iam content.

2479
02:28:44.470 --> 02:28:48.370
And ours with thine,befall what fortune will.

2480
02:28:48.370 --> 02:28:51.400
Good uncle, take you inthis barbarous Moor,

2481
02:28:51.400 --> 02:28:54.270
this ravenous tiger, thisaccursed devil.

2482
02:28:54.270 --> 02:28:56.030
Let him receive nosustenance.

2483
02:28:56.030 --> 02:28:58.230
Fetter him till he be broughtunto the empress' face

2484
02:28:58.230 --> 02:29:03.170
for testimony of her foulproceedings.

2485
02:29:03.170 --> 02:29:05.670
And see the ambush of ourfriends be strong.

2486
02:29:05.670 --> 02:29:08.030
I fear the emperor meansno good to us.

2487
02:29:11.470 --> 02:29:14.530
Some devil whisper cursesin my ear

2488
02:29:14.530 --> 02:29:17.500
and prompt me that mytongue may utter forth

2489
02:29:17.500 --> 02:29:20.470
the venomous malice of myswelling heart!

2490
02:29:20.470 --> 02:29:25.000
Away, inhuman dog,unhallowed slave!

2491
02:29:25.000 --> 02:29:31.870
Sirs, help our uncle toconvey him in.

2492
02:29:31.870 --> 02:29:34.570
The trumpets show theemperor is at hand.

2493
02:29:56.930 --> 02:29:59.530
What, hath the firmamentmore suns than one?

2494
02:29:59.530 --> 02:30:02.130
What boots it thee to canthyself a sun?

2495
02:30:02.130 --> 02:30:05.000
Rome's emperor, andnephew, break the parle.

2496
02:30:05.000 --> 02:30:08.500
These quarrels must bequietly debated.

2497
02:30:08.500 --> 02:30:11.230
The feast is ready whichthe careful Titus

2498
02:30:11.230 --> 02:30:14.000
hath ordained to anhonorable end,

2499
02:30:14.000 --> 02:30:16.870
for peace, for love, forleague, and good to Rome.

2500
02:30:16.870 --> 02:30:20.600
Please you, therefore, drawnigh and take your places.

2501
02:30:20.600 --> 02:30:22.600
Marcus, we will.

2502
02:31:02.470 --> 02:31:04.100
Welcome, my lord.

2503
02:31:04.100 --> 02:31:07.030
Welcome, dread queen.

2504
02:31:07.030 --> 02:31:09.970
Welcome, ye warlike Goths.

2505
02:31:09.970 --> 02:31:11.600
Welcome, Lucius.

2506
02:31:11.600 --> 02:31:13.630
And welcome all.

2507
02:31:13.630 --> 02:31:16.900
Although the cheer be poor,'twill fill your stomachs.

2508
02:31:16.900 --> 02:31:18.900
Please you eat of it.

2509
02:32:21.130 --> 02:32:24.200
Why art thou thus attired,Andronicus?

2510
02:32:24.200 --> 02:32:26.500
Because I would be sure tohave all well

2511
02:32:26.500 --> 02:32:29.870
to entertain Your Highnessand your empress.

2512
02:32:29.870 --> 02:32:32.500
We are beholding to you,good Andronicus.

2513
02:32:32.500 --> 02:32:35.530
And if Your Highness knewmy heart, you were.

2514
02:33:47.930 --> 02:33:51.430
My lord the emperor,resolve me this:

2515
02:33:51.430 --> 02:33:55.300
was it well done of rashVirginius

2516
02:33:55.300 --> 02:33:58.230
to slay his daughter withhis own right hand

2517
02:33:58.230 --> 02:34:04.570
because she was enforced,stained, and deflowered?

2518
02:34:04.570 --> 02:34:06.670
It was, Andronicus.

2519
02:34:06.670 --> 02:34:10.400
Your reason, mighty lord.

2520
02:34:10.400 --> 02:34:12.930
Because the girl shouldnot survive her shame

2521
02:34:12.930 --> 02:34:16.900
and by her presence stillrenew his sorrows.

2522
02:34:16.900 --> 02:34:23.800
A reason mighty, strong,and effectual

2523
02:34:23.800 --> 02:34:29.930
a pattern, precedent, andlively warrant

2524
02:34:29.930 --> 02:34:36.030
for me, most wretched, toperform the like.

2525
02:34:48.100 --> 02:34:56.670
Die, die, Lavinia, and thyshame with thee;

2526
02:34:56.670 --> 02:35:00.300
and with thy shame thyfather's sorrow die!

2527
02:35:00.300 --> 02:35:02.930
What hast thou done,unnatural and unkind?

2528
02:35:02.930 --> 02:35:08.330
Killed her for whom mytears have made me blind.

2529
02:35:08.330 --> 02:35:11.830
I am as woeful asVirginius was

2530
02:35:11.830 --> 02:35:15.800
and have a thousand timesmore cause than he

2531
02:35:15.800 --> 02:35:18.600
to do this outrage.

2532
02:35:18.600 --> 02:35:21.730
And it now is done.

2533
02:35:21.730 --> 02:35:24.370
What, was she ravished?

2534
02:35:24.370 --> 02:35:26.630
Tell who did the deed.

2535
02:35:26.630 --> 02:35:28.870
Will it please you eat?

2536
02:35:28.870 --> 02:35:31.370
Will it please YourHighness feed?

2537
02:35:31.370 --> 02:35:34.400
Why hast thou slain thineonly daughter thus?

2538
02:35:34.400 --> 02:35:37.270
Not I; 'twas Chiron andDemetrius.

2539
02:35:37.270 --> 02:35:39.370
They ravished her, and cutaway her tongue,

2540
02:35:39.370 --> 02:35:43.400
and they, 'twas they thatdid her all this wrong.

2541
02:35:43.400 --> 02:35:45.170
Go, fetch them hither tous presently.

2542
02:35:45.170 --> 02:35:47.830
Why, there they are, bothbaked in this pie

2543
02:35:47.830 --> 02:35:50.230
whereof their motherdaintily hath fed,

2544
02:35:50.230 --> 02:35:54.330
eating the flesh that sheherself hath bred.

2545
02:35:54.330 --> 02:36:00.470
'Tis true, 'tis true: witnessmy knife's sharp point.

2546
02:36:00.470 --> 02:36:04.870
Die, frantic wretch, forthis accursed deed!

2547
02:36:08.330 --> 02:36:11.730
Can the son's eye beholdhis father bleed?

2548
02:36:11.730 --> 02:36:15.630
There's meed for meed,death for a deadly deed!

2549
02:36:20.600 --> 02:36:25.370
You sad-faced men, peopleand sons of Rome,

2550
02:36:25.370 --> 02:36:28.670
by uproars severed as aflight of fowl

2551
02:36:28.670 --> 02:36:32.600
scattered by winds andhigh tempestuous gusts,

2552
02:36:32.600 --> 02:36:36.030
O, let me teach you how toknit again

2553
02:36:36.030 --> 02:36:39.970
this scattered corn intoone mutual sheaf,

2554
02:36:39.970 --> 02:36:42.630
these broken limbs againinto one body,

2555
02:36:42.630 --> 02:36:46.000
lest Rome herself be baneunto herself

2556
02:36:46.000 --> 02:36:48.830
and she whom mightykingdoms curtsy to,

2557
02:36:48.830 --> 02:36:51.500
like a forlorn anddesperate castaway,

2558
02:36:51.500 --> 02:36:55.230
do shameful execution onherself.

2559
02:36:55.230 --> 02:36:57.770
But if my frosty signs andchaps of age,

2560
02:36:57.770 --> 02:37:00.670
grave witnesses of trueexperience,

2561
02:37:00.670 --> 02:37:03.170
cannot induce you toattend my words,

2562
02:37:03.170 --> 02:37:08.200
speak, Rome's dear friend,as erst our ancestor,

2563
02:37:08.200 --> 02:37:11.030
when with his solemntongue he did discourse

2564
02:37:11.030 --> 02:37:13.330
to love-sick Dido's sadattending ear

2565
02:37:13.330 --> 02:37:15.870
the story of that balefulburning night,

2566
02:37:15.870 --> 02:37:19.830
when subtle Greeks surprisedKing Priam's Troy.

2567
02:37:19.830 --> 02:37:23.700
Tell us what Sinon hathbewitched our ears,

2568
02:37:23.700 --> 02:37:25.770
and who hath brought thefatal engine in

2569
02:37:25.770 --> 02:37:31.470
that gives our Troy, ourRome, the civil wound.

2570
02:37:31.470 --> 02:37:35.730
My heart is not compact offlint nor steel,

2571
02:37:35.730 --> 02:37:38.770
nor can I utter all ourbitter griefs,

2572
02:37:38.770 --> 02:37:42.000
but floods of tears willdrown my oratory

2573
02:37:42.000 --> 02:37:44.670
and break my utterance,even in the time

2574
02:37:44.670 --> 02:37:46.630
when it should move ye toattend me most,

2575
02:37:46.630 --> 02:37:50.630
and force you tocommiseration.

2576
02:37:50.630 --> 02:37:53.070
Here's Rome's youngcaptain.

2577
02:37:53.070 --> 02:37:55.170
Let him tell the tale

2578
02:37:55.170 --> 02:37:59.870
while I stand by and weepto hear him speak.

2579
02:37:59.870 --> 02:38:04.500
Then, gracious auditory,be it known to you

2580
02:38:04.500 --> 02:38:06.400
that Chiron and the damnedDemetrius

2581
02:38:06.400 --> 02:38:09.170
were they that murderedour emperor's brother.

2582
02:38:09.170 --> 02:38:13.030
And they it were thatravished our sister.

2583
02:38:13.030 --> 02:38:16.770
For their fell faults ourbrothers were beheaded,

2584
02:38:16.770 --> 02:38:21.330
our father's tears despised,and basely cozened

2585
02:38:21.330 --> 02:38:23.800
of that true hand thatfought Rome's quarrel out

2586
02:38:23.800 --> 02:38:26.570
and sent her enemies untothe grave.

2587
02:38:26.570 --> 02:38:31.570
Lastly, myself unkindlybanished,

2588
02:38:31.570 --> 02:38:35.900
the gates shut on me, andturned weeping out

2589
02:38:35.900 --> 02:38:38.200
to beg relief among Rome'senemies,

2590
02:38:38.200 --> 02:38:40.930
who drowned their enmityin my true tears

2591
02:38:40.930 --> 02:38:45.270
and oped their arms toembrace me as a friend.

2592
02:38:45.270 --> 02:38:47.970
I am the turned forth, beit known to you,

2593
02:38:47.970 --> 02:38:51.100
that have preserved herwelfare in my blood

2594
02:38:51.100 --> 02:38:53.670
and from her bosom tookthe enemy's point,

2595
02:38:53.670 --> 02:38:56.830
sheathing the steel in myadventurous body.

2596
02:38:56.830 --> 02:39:00.170
Alas; you know I am novaunter, I.

2597
02:39:00.170 --> 02:39:03.730
My scars can witness, dumbalthough they are,

2598
02:39:03.730 --> 02:39:07.130
that my report is just andfull of truth.

2599
02:39:07.130 --> 02:39:10.070
But, soft; methinks I dodigress too much,

2600
02:39:10.070 --> 02:39:12.400
citing my worthlesspraise.

2601
02:39:12.400 --> 02:39:14.770
O, pardon me.

2602
02:39:14.770 --> 02:39:19.630
For when no friends areby, men praise themselves.

2603
02:39:19.630 --> 02:39:23.430
Now is my turn to speak.

2604
02:39:23.430 --> 02:39:26.100
Behold the child.

2605
02:39:26.100 --> 02:39:28.630
Of this was Tamoradelivered,

2606
02:39:28.630 --> 02:39:30.970
the issue of anirreligious Moor,

2607
02:39:30.970 --> 02:39:33.870
chief architect andplotter of these woes.

2608
02:39:33.870 --> 02:39:36.730
The villain is alive inTitus' house,

2609
02:39:36.730 --> 02:39:42.730
and as he is, to witnessthis is true.

2610
02:39:42.730 --> 02:39:47.400
Now judge what cause hadTitus to revenge

2611
02:39:47.400 --> 02:39:51.130
these wrongs unspeakable,past patience,

2612
02:39:51.130 --> 02:39:54.900
or more than any livingman could bear.

2613
02:39:54.900 --> 02:39:57.570
Now have you heard thetruth.

2614
02:39:57.570 --> 02:39:59.330
What say you, Romans?

2615
02:39:59.330 --> 02:40:02.500
Have we done aught amiss,show us wherein,

2616
02:40:02.500 --> 02:40:04.830
and, from the place whereyou behold us pleading,

2617
02:40:04.830 --> 02:40:06.800
the poor remainder ofAndronici

2618
02:40:06.800 --> 02:40:10.270
will, hand in hand, allheadlong hurl ourselves

2619
02:40:10.270 --> 02:40:13.000
and on the ragged stonesbeat forth our souls

2620
02:40:13.000 --> 02:40:17.500
and make a mutual closureof our house.

2621
02:40:17.500 --> 02:40:19.700
Speak, Romans, speak.

2622
02:40:19.700 --> 02:40:23.730
And if you say we shall,lo, hand in hand,

2623
02:40:23.730 --> 02:40:26.400
Lucius and I will fall.

2624
02:40:26.400 --> 02:40:31.130
Come, Marcus, come, thoureverend man of Rome,

2625
02:40:31.130 --> 02:40:34.900
and bring our emperorgently in thy hand,

2626
02:40:34.900 --> 02:40:36.930
Lucius our emperor;

2627
02:40:36.930 --> 02:40:40.700
for well I know the commonvoice do cry it shall be so.

2628
02:40:40.700 --> 02:40:47.500
Lucius, all hail, Rome'sroyal emperor!

2629
02:40:47.500 --> 02:40:49.570
Go to old Titus' sorrowfulhouse

2630
02:40:49.570 --> 02:40:51.700
and hither hale thatmisbelieving Moor

2631
02:40:51.700 --> 02:40:53.730
to be adjudged somedireful slaughtering death

2632
02:40:53.730 --> 02:40:57.530
as punishment for his mostwicked life.

2633
02:40:57.530 --> 02:41:02.970
Lucius, all hail, Rome'sgracious governor!

2634
02:41:08.500 --> 02:41:10.730
Thanks, gentle Romans.

2635
02:41:10.730 --> 02:41:13.400
May I govern so to healRome's harms

2636
02:41:13.400 --> 02:41:15.370
and wipe away her woe.

2637
02:41:15.370 --> 02:41:18.970
But gentle people, give meaim awhile,

2638
02:41:18.970 --> 02:41:21.700
for nature puts me to aheavy task.

2639
02:41:21.700 --> 02:41:26.270
Stand all aloof, but,uncle, draw you near

2640
02:41:26.270 --> 02:41:28.870
to shed obsequious tearsupon this trunk.

2641
02:41:34.170 --> 02:41:38.570
O, take this warm kiss onthy pale cold lips,

2642
02:41:38.570 --> 02:41:42.930
these sorrowful drops uponthy blood-stained face

2643
02:41:42.930 --> 02:41:46.270
the last true duties ofthy noble son.

2644
02:41:48.970 --> 02:41:53.200
Tear for tear and lovingkiss for kiss

2645
02:41:53.200 --> 02:41:56.770
thy brother Marcus tenderson thy lips.

2646
02:41:58.530 --> 02:42:00.830
O, were the sum of thesethat I should pay

2647
02:42:00.830 --> 02:42:05.900
countless and infinite,yet would I pay them.

2648
02:42:05.900 --> 02:42:08.430
Come hither, boy.

2649
02:42:08.430 --> 02:42:16.830
Come, come, and learn ofus to melt in showers.

2650
02:42:16.830 --> 02:42:19.470
Thy grandsire loved theewell.

2651
02:42:19.470 --> 02:42:22.930
Many a time he danced theeon his knee,

2652
02:42:22.930 --> 02:42:26.630
sung thee asleep, hisloving breast thy pillow.

2653
02:42:26.630 --> 02:42:29.270
Many a story hath he toldto thee

2654
02:42:29.270 --> 02:42:32.030
and bid thee bear hispretty tales in mind

2655
02:42:32.030 --> 02:42:34.400
and talk of them when hewas dead and gone.

2656
02:42:37.070 --> 02:42:39.630
How many thousand timeshave these poor lips,

2657
02:42:39.630 --> 02:42:43.300
when they were living,warmed themselves on thine.

2658
02:42:43.300 --> 02:42:46.530
O, now, sweet boy, givethem their latest kiss.

2659
02:42:46.530 --> 02:42:50.330
Bid him farewell; commithim to the grave.

2660
02:42:50.330 --> 02:42:54.370
Do them that kindness andtake leave of them.

2661
02:42:54.370 --> 02:42:57.600
Grandsire, Grandsire, evenwith all my heart,

2662
02:42:57.600 --> 02:43:00.570
were I were dead so youdid live again.

2663
02:43:00.570 --> 02:43:03.900
O Lord, I cannot speak tohim for weeping.

2664
02:43:03.900 --> 02:43:06.070
My tears will choke me, ifI ope my mouth.

2665
02:43:06.070 --> 02:43:09.970
You sad Andronici, havedone with woes.

2666
02:43:09.970 --> 02:43:12.370
Give sentence on theexecrable wretch

2667
02:43:12.370 --> 02:43:15.070
who hath been breeder ofthese dire events.

2668
02:43:32.130 --> 02:43:36.500
Set him breast-deep inearth and famish him.

2669
02:43:36.500 --> 02:43:40.800
There let him stand andrave and cry for food.

2670
02:43:40.800 --> 02:43:42.430
If any one relieves orpities him,

2671
02:43:42.430 --> 02:43:43.970
for the offence he dies.

2672
02:43:43.970 --> 02:43:45.600
This is our doom.

2673
02:43:48.470 --> 02:43:53.700
Ah, why should wrath bemute and fury dumb?

2674
02:43:53.700 --> 02:43:56.930
I am no baby, I, that withbase prayers

2675
02:43:56.930 --> 02:43:59.500
I should repent the evilsI have done.

2676
02:43:59.500 --> 02:44:02.330
Ten thousand worse thanever yet I did

2677
02:44:02.330 --> 02:44:05.170
would I perform, if Imight have my will.

2678
02:44:05.170 --> 02:44:09.130
If one good deed in all mylife I did,

2679
02:44:09.130 --> 02:44:12.230
I do repent it from myvery soul.

2680
02:44:21.400 --> 02:44:24.430
Some loving friends conveythe emperor hence

2681
02:44:24.430 --> 02:44:27.330
and give him burial in hisfather's grave.

2682
02:44:27.330 --> 02:44:30.930
My father and Laviniashall forthwith be closed

2683
02:44:30.930 --> 02:44:33.770
in our household'smonument.

2684
02:44:33.770 --> 02:44:37.700
As for that ravenoustiger, Tamora

2685
02:44:37.700 --> 02:44:44.570
no funeral rite nor man inmourning weed.

2686
02:44:44.570 --> 02:44:46.870
No mournful bell shallring her burial,

2687
02:44:46.870 --> 02:44:52.000
but throw her forth tobeasts and birds to prey.

2688
02:44:52.000 --> 02:44:56.470
Her life was beastly anddevoid of pity,

2689
02:44:56.470 --> 02:45:04.270
and being dead, let birdson her take pity.

